# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: bmw
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:bmw/1975-12-hours-of-sebring] The **Sebring '75 Twelve Hours of Endurance**, was the second round of the **1975 IMSA GT Championship** and was held at the Sebring International Raceway on March 21, 1975.
[src:bmw/1975-12-hours-of-sebring] 25 BMW Motorsport BMW 3.0 CSL driven by British driver Brian Redman, Canadian born Australian Allan Moffat, American Sam Posey, and West German Hans-Joachim Stuck.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The **Nürburgring 24 Hours** is a 24-hour annual touring car and GT endurance racing event that takes place on a combination of the Nordschleife ("North Loop") and the GP-Strecke ("Grand Prix track") circuits of the Nürburgring in Rhineland-Palatinate, Germany.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Held since 1970, the over 25.3 km (15.7 mi) lap length allows more than 200 cars and over 700 drivers to participate.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Starting in 2024, the event has been officially named **ADAC RAVENOL 24h Nürburgring** for sponsorship reasons.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Furthermore, the 2024 season of the race was included in the Intercontinental GT Challenge calendar.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Officially called "ADAC 24h Rennen Nürburgring" in German ('ADAC 24 hour Race Nürburgring'), it was introduced in 1970 by the ADAC as an official race, unlike the earlier endurance contests that covered 12, 24 (in 1961 and 1967), 36, 84 and even 96 hours, like the Marathon de la Route.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This substitute for the Liège-Rome-Liège and Liège-Sofia-Liège rallies was held on the Nürburgring from 1965 to 1971.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] It is similar to the Spa 24 Hours, which had been introduced in 1924, following the 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The ADAC had held its first 1000 km Nürburgring sports car racing event in 1953.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] As the 1000 km Spa had been introduced in 1966, the 24h at the Ring gave both circuits a pair of endurance racing events at very long tracks, at least until Spa was shortened in 1979.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Just like the VLN series with its 4-hour races, the 24h race is mainly aimed at amateurs, in order to fill a starting field of around 200 cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Unlike the VLN races, the 24h is officially an international event, with trilingual (French, German and English, since 2024 because SRO regulations are in French) organization and documentation.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Entry fees are due, in 2010 these were €7,508 per car, of which €3,000 was an advance payment for fuel.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Typical entries range from second hand standard road cars to European Touring Car Championship vehicles and GT3 sports cars like the Porsche 911 GT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The participation of manufactures and professional teams and drivers has varied over the decades.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] As this section and its large paved run-off areas was useful as extra paddock zone for the competitors of the support races, it is bypassed with a sharp Z-shape chicane since 2005 for a 25.3 km (15.7 mi) track length.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The number of cars starting is limited to 150 as of 2024, driven by up to 600 drivers, as 2, 3 or 4 can share a car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] One driver is allowed to drive 150 minutes non-stop, and can enter on two cars, yet a rest time of at least 2 hours has to be observed between two turns of the same driver.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race is typically held in May or June on the Ascension Day or Corpus Christi holiday.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2020 race was postponed to September and held with limited spectators, restricted to the Grand Prix course area (initially planned to be held behind closed doors) due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2024 race set a new shortest distance record of just 50 laps with less than 10 hours of racing due to rain and overnight fog; the 2023 race set a new longest distance run for the race, as well as the first win for Ferrari.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The Nurburgring 24 Hours is known for its wide variety of cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2023, 135 cars in 20 classes were entered.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race has often seen cars that are rarely used in other international racing events.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Examples include Fiat Cinquecentos in the 1990s, a Volkswagen Caravelle in 2000, the P4/5 Competizione in the 2010s, or a 1988 Opel Manta that has raced from 1994 to 2023.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the length of the track, the Nürburgring 24 Hours has unusual safety procedures compared to other modern professional endurance races.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Safety cars are not used except during red flag and ensuing restart situations, double yellow flags indicate a local speed limit of 120 km/h (75 mph), and code 60 flags, used locally for incidents warranting a safety car on shorter tracks, limit the speed to 60 km/h (37 mph).
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] It is common for course cars and vehicle recovery trucks to travel around the course under local double yellow flags.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Since 2015; competitors must hold a valid "DMSB Permit Nordschleife", a license to race specifically on the Nordschleife section of the Nürburgring.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] They must also take part in 3 races on the track within the last 2 calendar years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Closing speeds between the fastest and slowest car classes is a common concern, as the track has many blind crests and corners.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2023, a serious accident happened between a Porsche 911 GT3 R and a Dacia Logan SP3 - the slowest car in the field that year - after the Porsche hit the Logan at the high-speed Stefan-Bellof-S and sent it into the barriers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The unpredictable Eifel weather is also a danger.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Heavy rain and fog stopped the race for several hours in 2018, 2020 and 2021, while the 2016 race was red-flagged due to an unusual hailstorm storm that caused a series of crashes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In 2001, driver Christian Peruzzi was killed after a practice accident in an Alfa Romeo 147.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The Nürburgring 24 Hours has several support races on Thursday, Friday and Saturday, some happening on the GP Track, some happening on the Nordschleife only, some happening on the combined track.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] As of 2023, the support program includes the Rundstrecken Challenge Nürburgring, and several historic touring cars and GT races.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The last support race is the ADAC 24h-Classic, a 3 hour race on the combined track on Saturday morning, several hours before the 24 Hours race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Unlike the two previous races, held on Ascension Day weekend in May in rainy and very cold weather, the 2006 event was run in warm, sunny and dry conditions on Corpus Christi (feast) weekend of June 17–18.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Pure factory teams that challenged for the overall win were absent, yet Aston Martin and Maserati had entered factory-backed cars to promote their products, reminding of three overall wins each in the 1000 km Nürburgring decades ago.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The Aston Martin car with Aston CEO Ulrich Bez finished 4th in class and 24th overall.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to good conditions and stiff competition by similar cars, a new overall distance record (3,832 km (2,381 mi) in 151 laps) was scored by the Porsche 996 GT3 of Manthey Racing that already had been the best privateer team in the previous three years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This team is partially supported by Porsche, though, with factory drivers, a 3.8L 500 PS (370 kW; 490 hp) engine and a sequential gear box.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Second place finishers Jürgen Alzen/Uwe Alzen/Klaus Ludwig/Christian Abt of team *Jürgen Alzen Motorsport* was only one lap down and have beaten the old record, too.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] They used a conventional gear box and a privately built 3.8L 500PS engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The third of three fastest Porsche, the *Wolfgang Land Motorsport* 911, had suffered a fiery failure of its standard 3.6L Porsche 911 GT3-RSR race engine after 21 hours, yet was classified as 14th with 133 laps.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] A remarkable 5th place overall was scored by a BMW 120d from Schubert Motors, which had roughly half the power of some of the cars it beat.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] It was driven by Claudia Hürtgen (2005 VLN champion), Marc Hennerici (2005 privateer WTCC champion), Johannes Stuck (son of Hans-Joachim Stuck) and team owner Torsten Schubert.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] For the 2007 event held on Corpus Christi weekend of June 7–10, more than 260 teams had applied for the 220 race entries.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Prior to the start which had been scheduled for 15:00, an approaching thunderstorm made the organizers delay the beginning of the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Lightning struck the camp of fans, injuring several, while heavy rain made the track muddy.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] At 16:51, the race was started after two laps behind a safety car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Veteran Klaus Ludwig at the wheel of the Aston Martin DBRS9 which had been given the number 007 took the lead in wet conditions, but hesitating too long with the change to dry tyres, the favorite Manthey team took the lead in their new Porsche 997 GT3-RSR.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] More weather-related drama occurred in the night, when the race was interrupted due to fog for six hours, making the race 18 hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] When the race resumed, the Land Porsche 996 GT3-RSR was slightly damaged when hitting the back of the Manthey car, and the Aston Martin engine failed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Thus the Manthey team could easily defend its 2006 victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The reliable, yet no more fast enough Zakspeed Dodge Viper GTS-R came in second, with the Alzen brothers Porsche Cayman in 4th and the BMW Z4 M-Coupe 5th.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Remarkable performances were the top ten finishes of a VW Golf 5, an Opel Astra GTC and a BMW 130i, and the 13th place of a Hyundai Coupe V6 piloted by ex British Touring Car racer Peter Cate.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] For the 2008, over 270 cars were entered, of which only 230 could be accepted.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race began in sunny weather with drama for the favorite Porsche teams of Manthey and Land, losing time with a leaky radiator and a tire failure, and the new Alzen 997 Turbo and the Zakspeed Viper battling for the lead.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] After the Viper was out, only the BMW Z4 (E85) of Claudia Hürtgen, pole setter and winner of the recent VLN race, could challenge the Porsche armada and lead for some laps, but it crashed during the night.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Manthey could catch up and win the race for a third time in a row, with the winning car of 2006 (a 996 model) finishing 2nd.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The triumph made the team mechanics cut off Olaf Manthey's famous moustache tips.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Sabine Schmitz came in third, also on a Porsche 997.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] A strong showing among the high powered cars gave the three new Volkswagen Scirocco, finishing 9th and 12th, with veteran Hans Joachim Stuck driving both cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] For 2009, the organizers announced that they wanted to reduce the gap in speeds, by not accepting small capacity cars any more, and by slowing down the fastest classes, SP7 and SP8.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Also, the new FIA GT3 and FIA GT4 classes were adopted, called SP9 and SP10.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Some of the new rules are controversial, especially the fact that instead of the regular fuel pumps as used in any public station, the top teams have to use expensive equipment designed to equal the times needed to refill, meaning that an economic car is punished compared to a thirsty car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the various rule changes, some teams have declined to take part, namely Zakspeed with their Viper.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Probably also due to the economic crisis, the number of entries was much lower than in previous years, with only 170 cars starting the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Surprisingly, the pole was set by a Ford GT, followed closely by the four factory-entered Audi R8 LMS and two Porsche GT3 of the Manthey team.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] They decided to enter their well-known RSR, which is basically a GT2 car, but now has about 70 hp less due to new air restrictors, and also a *997 GT3 Cup S*, the version Porsche homologated for FIA GT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] For the first 19 hours, two of the Audis and the two Manthey Porsche battled for the lead within a lap, the pace likely to result in a new distance record.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The Manthey #1 had been punished for approaching an accident site too quickly and had to wait 3 minutes in the box, but the decision was reverted later based on data logging evidence, with the lost time deducted from the results.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Around 11:30, the #99 Audi which had a narrow lead was stopped by suspension problems.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Following repairs this car finished in 5th position.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This left the #97 Audi in second, and with the win in its class, 5 minutes behind the overall winner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2010 event on Ascension Day weekend of May 13–16 saw a return of most prominent entries, except the Ford GT, as team Raeder had discontinued this project.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] To give teams time to rest or for repairs before the race, the night practice was scheduled on Thursday evening.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In cold and wet conditions, the Farnbacher-entered Ferrari F430 GTC set the best lap time before the session was red-flagged due to fog.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In Friday afternoon qualifying, held in fair weather, it crashed out and was barely repaired in time for the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Four of the five factory-backed Audi R8 LMS (officially entered by "customers", which happen to be the Audi-DTM-teams Phoenix Racing and Abt Sportsline) occupied the first four places on the grid, with Marco Werner setting pole at 8:24.753 with a new record average speed of 181 km/h (112 mph).
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] With lap times around 8:29, three of Porsche's new SP9/GT3-class cars occupied places 5 to 7, two of them entered by four-time winner Team Manthey, which had chosen to let the #1 car do only a single lap.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] BMW had entered two of their ALMS BMW M3 GT2, run by Schnitzer Motorsport.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Due to the modifications that include a transaxle gear box, they do not comply to the standard rules set of SP classes and their "Balance of Performance".
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Along with a factory-entered Porsche GT3 Hybrid, the M3s were classed as E1-XP entries (the E1-XP class was actually intended for experimental factory entries).
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The better BMW and the Hybrid posted times of 8:32 and 8:34 in qualifying.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Save for the 16th placed GT3-class Dodge Viper, only several other Porsche, Audi R8 and V8-powered BMW Z4 (E89) have qualified in the top 20, with times up to 8:47, which earns them a blue flash light that is supposed to facilitate passing of the approx.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Porsche test driver Walter Röhrl had intended to enter on a standard road legal Porsche 911 GT3 RS, but had to withdraw for health reasons from the team that comprises racers Roland Asch and Patrick Simon, plus journalists Horst von Saurma and Chris Harris.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The car, entered in cooperation with sport auto (Germany), is registered as S-GO 2400, and was driven from Weissach to Nürburg.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] It has qualified with 9:15, 42nd overall, and 9th among the 17 SP7 class entrants, only beaten by its race-prepped Porsche 997 siblings.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race was started on Saturday 3 p.m. in sunny but cold weather.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Already on the Grand Prix track, the #1 Manthey Porsche driven by five-time winner Marcel Tiemann passed all Audis, taking the lead and pulling away about 100 m (330 ft) before catching up in lap 2 with the slowest cars of the third group, which were still in their first lap.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] After lap 3, three Porsche lead ahead of three Audi, a BMW M3 and the Hybrid-Porsche, which due to his larger range could take the lead after the others pitted.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #1 Manthey Porsche led by a couple of minutes until got involved in a collision after seven hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] At halftime, the race is on pace to another distance record, with the Audi #99 leading by a small margin ahead of the Hybrid Porsche, the only remaining representative of his brand in the top 8, which used to be dominated by Porsche in recent years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Places three to eight were occupied by three Audi R8, two BMW, and, rather surprisingly, on p 5 the Ferrari which had started in row 21.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The Porsches that occupy most places up to 15th were followed by the CNG-powered Volkswagen Scirocco GT24, the road-legal Porsche GT3 RS and a Nissan Z33.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] On Sunday morning, the #99 Audi needed a rear axle change, and with less than 5 hours to go, also the second place #2 Audi failed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This left the Hybrid Porsche in a one lap lead ahead of the #25 BMW GT2 with gearbox woes and the Ferrari, until also the Porsche stopped with less than two hours to go.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The BMW made it to the finish, giving Pedro Lamy a record-tying fifth win ahead of Ferrari and Audi.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The best Porsche, entered by Alzen, finished only sixth, six laps ahead of the Falken Nissan and the road legal GT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The SP4 class was won by 4 Argentinian drivers in the BMW 325i E92 Coupe of Motorsport Team Sorg Rennsport.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This was the first victory for an Argentinian team at the Nürburgring 24 Hours race and the first Argentinian team to compete in the Nürburgring since Juan Manuel Fangio.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] With Corpus Christi weekend being rather late in 2011 on June 23–26, the 2011 event was held two weeks after the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The first five VLN races of 2011 were won by a factory-entered BMW, a GT3-class Mercedes SLS, a new Ferrari 458, the Hybrid Porsche GT3 and finally an Audi R8 LMS, so at least these five different brands were expected to challenge for the overall win in the 24 hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] In the first qualifying session, the Hankook-sponsored Farnbacher-Ferrari used soft tyres and was about 7 seconds faster than the competitors, lapping at an average speed of over 181 km/h, the fastest since 1983, when it was still run with prototype cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] This earned the team the pole position, but also an extra weight of 25 kg in the pre-race update of the ‘Balance of Performance’.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] After a few hours in changing weather conditions, the team retired the ‘R’ to focus on the ‘RSR’ which already had won three times since 2007.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Without any problems, it went on to win its fourth Nürburgring 24 Hours, with a new distance record of 156 laps.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Second place was taken by another GT2-spec car, the #1 factory BMW M3 GT which had won in 2010.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Five GT3 cars of Audi and Mercedes followed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The SP8/GT2-class #2 Ferrari had run into early problems, but set the fastest race lap in the final hours, finishing 8th and James Glickenhaus’ P4/5 Competizione finished 39th, second in the E1-XP2.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] After 2010 Sorg Rennsport took the victory in class SP4 again.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Gianvito Rossi, Diego Romanini, Alfredo Varini and Alexander Rappold have been the only team in that class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2012 event was the first to have a "Top 40" qualifying shootout for the 40 fastest cars on the starting grid, which took place on the Friday after the first 2 qualifying sessions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #3 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2013 race saw Aston Martin's hydrogen powered car run the first ever zero-emissions lap of the circuit.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race also saw the first ever win for a Mercedes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #9 Team Black Falcon won the race in a Mercedes-AMG GT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2014 race set a new record for the total distance driven during a Nürburgring 24-hour race with 4,035 km (159 laps) driven by the top two cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #28 Audi Sport Team WRT won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 AMG-Team Black Falcon won the race in a Mercedes-AMG GT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #29 Audi Sport Team Land / Montaplast Land-Motorsport Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #912 Manthey Racing Team won the race in a Porsche 911 GT3 R.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #4 Phoenix Racing Team won the race in an Audi R8 LMS Evo.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Traditionally held in May, it was announced on March that the race will be postponed to September 24–27 due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The event was initially planned to be held behind closed doors, but later a limited amount of spectators were admitted.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] Rowe Racing (BMW M6 GT3) won the event, the first for BMW in 10 years, although the race was interrupted for most of the night due to inclement weather.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 2021 race was won by the Porsche-based Manthey Racing, who was forced to sit out the previous year's race due to COVID-19 concerns involving the team crew.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] A new record low of 58 laps (and less than ten hours of actual racing) was covered, as the race was once again interrupted for most of the night due to inclement weather.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The 50th anniversary 2022 race took place on 28–29 May 2022.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] A total of 159 laps were completed by the winning car #15 from Scherer Sport Team Phoenix.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The #30 Frikadelli Racing Team won the race in a Ferrari 296 GT3 completing a total of 162 laps.
[src:bmw/24-hours-nürburgring] The race set a new distance record and also marks Ferrari's first ever Nürburgring 24 Hours victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The **24 Hours of Daytona**, also known as the **Rolex 24 at Daytona** for sponsorship reasons, is a 24-hour sports car endurance race held annually at Daytona International Speedway in Daytona Beach, Florida.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] It is run on the Sports Car Course layout, a 3.56-mile (5.73 km) combined road course that uses most of the tri-oval plus an infield road course.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race has about 60 different cars competing for victory across multiple classes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] With multiple drivers “Each team trades shifts between three and five drivers”.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race is held on the last weekend of January or first weekend of February as part of Speedweeks, making it the first major automobile race of the year in North America.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race is sanctioned by IMSA and is the first race of the season for the IMSA SportsCar Championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race has borne the names of several sponsors over the years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Since 1992, Rolex has been the title sponsor of the race, replacing Sunbank, which replaced Pepsi in 1984.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Winning drivers of all classes receive a Rolex Daytona watch, a tradition that started back in 1964 for the Daytona Continental.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The reason behind racers winning a watch is because back then “chronographs were really “tool watches” for those in the racing industry” used for time purposes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race is known as a leg of the informal Triple Crown of endurance racing along with the 24 Hours of Le Mans and 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Since Rolex's sponsorship, winners also receive a Rolex watch as part of their prize at the end of the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Shortly after the track opened, on April 5, 1959, a six-hour/1000 kilometer USAC-FIA sports car race was held on the road course.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Count Antonio Von Dory and Roberto Mieres won the race in a Porsche, shortened to 560.07 miles (901.35 km) due to darkness.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race used a 3.81-mile layout, running clockwise.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This event is not considered to be part of the lineage of the eventual 24-hour race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1962, a 3-hour sports car race was introduced.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] First known as the **Daytona Continental**, it counted towards the FIA's new International Championship for GT Manufacturers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The first Continental was won by Dan Gurney, driving a 2.7L Coventry Climax-powered Lotus 19.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Gurney was a factory Porsche driver at the time, but the 1600-cc Porsche 718 was considered too small and slow for what amounted to a sprint race on a very fast course.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This was the case in the initial 1962 Daytona Continental (then 3 hours), in which Dan Gurney's Lotus 19 had established a lengthy lead when the engine failed with just minutes remaining.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Gurney stopped the car at the top of the banking, just short of the finish line.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] When the three hours had elapsed, Gurney simply cranked the steering wheel to the left (toward the bottom of the banking) and let gravity pull the car across the line, to not only salvage a finishing position, but actually win the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This led to the international rule requiring a car to cross the line under its own power in order to be classified.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1964, the event was expanded to 2,000 km (1,240 mi), doubling the classic 1000 km distance of races at Nürburgring, Spa and Monza.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The distance amounted to roughly half of the distance the 24 Hours of Le Mans winners covered at the time, and was similar in length to the 12 Hours of Sebring, which was also held in Florida in March.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Starting in 1966, the Daytona race was extended to the same 24-hour length as Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The first 24 Hour event in 1966 was won by Ken Miles and Lloyd Ruby driving a Ford Mk.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] 1966 also saw Suzy Dietrich enter the 24 Hours event, driving a Sunbeam Alpine with Janet Guthrie and Donna Mae Mims.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The trio finished 32nd and, along with another women's team in the race, became the first women's teams to finish an international-standard 24-hour race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] After having lost in 1966 at Daytona, Sebring and Le Mans to the Fords, the Ferrari P series prototypes staged a 1–2–3 side-by-side parade finish at the banked finish line in 1967.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The Ferrari 365 GTB/4 road car was given the unofficial name *Ferrari Daytona* in celebration of this victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Porsche repeated this show in their 1–2–3 win in the 1968 24 Hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] After the car of Gerhard Mitter had a big crash caused by tire failure in the banking, his teammate Rolf Stommelen supported the car of Vic Elford and Jochen Neerpasch.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] When the car of the longtime leaders Jo Siffert and Hans Herrmann dropped to second due to a technical problem, these two also joined the new leaders while continuing with their car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] So Porsche managed to put 5 of 8 drivers on the center of the podium, plus Jo Schlesser and Joe Buzzetta finishing in third place, with only Mitter being left out.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Lola finished 1–2 in the 1969 24 Hours of Daytona.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The winning car was the Penske Lola T70-Chevrolet of Mark Donohue and Chuck Parsons.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] 1970 saw the race with drivers strapped into their cars, and at the start, drove away.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Since 1971, races begin with rolling starts.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1972, the rules changed, limiting cars to only 3.0 liters instead of the previous 5.0 liters and made a weight limit for cars as well.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This caused Porsche to back out of the series for that year leading to a Ferrari victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1972, because of an FIA rule, the race was shortened to six hours, while the energy crisis led to the cancellation altogether in 1974.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The Sports Car Club of America sanctioning was replaced by the International Motor Sports Association in 1975.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1982 the race continued on as part of the IMSA GT Championship instead of WSC.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 1989, the race was delayed due to fog for four hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This was the longest time the race was paused due to fog.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The race has been paused due to fog multiple times.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In this time the cars are forced to follow a pace car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 2011, the race was delayed so long due to the fog that the pace car was forced to stop for gas.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 2014, the race saw a dramatic crash involving Memo Gidley who was driving the pole-sitter DP and Matteo Malucelli, an amateur driver in a Ferrari 458 of the GTD category that has never won a race in North American Endurance.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] At the time of the impact, Malucelli was driving at less than 30 mph and keeping on the track while cars were passing him at 150 mph.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Memo, who was side by side to another car couldn't have seen him and impacted front first.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The regular teams were expanded to three drivers in the 1970s.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Nowadays, four drivers compete typically because of the longer night driving.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In the professional-based DPi Prototype and ACO GTE classes, all four drivers are usually professionals.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In the ACO LMP2 and SRO Group GT3-based classes, many of these additional drivers are known as "amateur drivers," under current FIA specifications.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Amateur drivers are sportsman drivers that have built a career in a non-motorsport related occupation.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] These types of drivers are typically eligible for IMSA's Jim Trueman and Bob Akin awards, awarded to the top driver who is not a professional at the end of season.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] These amateur drivers or overage professional drivers (FIA Silver or Bronze are typically for amateur drivers but professional drivers over 55 are automatically classified at this level) are required in the car for a specific number of hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Most often, the fourth driver in all classes is a Daytona-only professional driver of renown that most often has won a major professional championship, such as Scott Dixon, Jeff Gordon, Fernando Alonso, Shane van Gisbergen and Kyle Busch.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Unlike the Le Mans event, the Daytona race is conducted entirely over a closed course within the speedway arena without the use of any public streets.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Most parts of the steep banking are included, interrupted with a chicane on the back straight and a sweeping, fast infield section which includes two hairpins.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Unlike Le Mans, the race is held in wintertime, when nights are at their longest.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] There are lights installed around the circuit for night racing, although the infield section is still not as well-lit as the main oval.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] However, the stadium lights are turned on only to a level of 20%, similar to the stadium lighting setup at Le Mans, with brighter lights around the pit straight, and decent lighting similar to street lights around the circuit.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The Grand Am series, though, is instead closely linked to NASCAR and the original ideas of IMSA and focused on controlled costs and close competition.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In order to make sports car racing less expensive than elsewhere, new rules were introduced in 2002.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The dedicated Daytona Prototypes (DP) used less expensive materials and technologies and the car's simple aerodynamics reduce the development and testing costs.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The DPs began racing in 2003 with six cars in the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Specialist chassis makers like Riley, Dallara, and Lola provided the DP cars for the teams and the engines are branded under the names of major car companies like Cadillac, Lexus, Ford, BMW, and Porsche.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] 2017 saw the introduction of the DPi prototypes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] These cars were based on LMP2 chassis with a custom engine and bodywork from a major manufacturer.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] For 2023, the race adopted the LMDh prototype specification, although Le Mans Hypercars were also permitted.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The series has also returned to the Grand Touring Prototype name from the 1980s.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 2023, the first hybrid car, an Acura ARX-06, won the Rolex 24 Hours at Daytona.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] This would be the first hybrid car to ever win the Rolex 24 Hours at Daytona.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] With these new hybrid cars, the IMSA has set regulations and even penalties if teams using these engines break these rules.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In order to ensure they don't break the rules they have monitors that monitor the total energy being used by the car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The new hybrid engines can help increase horsepower due to the electric battery and gas engine working together which can be an advantage in certain parts of the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Multiple manufacturers are now trying out hybrid cars for the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The Gran Turismo class cars at Daytona are closer to the road versions, similar to the GT3 class elsewhere.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] For example, the more standard Cup version of the Porsche 996 is used, instead of the usual RS/RSR racing versions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Recent Daytona entries also include BMW M3s and M6s, Porsche 911s, Chevy Camaros and Corvettes, Mazda RX-8s, Pontiac GTO.Rs, and Ferrari F430 Challenges.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The Audi R8 and the Ferrari 458 Italia debuted in the 50th anniversary of the race in 2012.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] From the era of the IMSA GTO and GTU until the 2015 rule changes, spaceframe cars clad in lookalike body panels to compete in GT (the new BMW M6, Chevrolet Camaro, and Mazda RX-8).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] These rules are similar to the old GTO specification, but with more restrictions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The intent of spaceframe cars is to allow teams to save money, especially after crashes, where teams can rebuild the cars for the next race at a much lower cost, or even redevelop cars, instead of having to write off an entire car after a crash or at the end of a year.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Starting in 2014 the GT Daytona class was restricted exclusively to Group GT3 cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Alongside this came the GTLM class, using LM GTE cars, similar to the WEC.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In 2022 the GTLM class was replaced by GTD Pro, using the same cars as GTD.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] A single GTLM car, the Corvette C8.R, was also permitted to compete in the class with its performance adjusted to the GTD cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] IMSA adapted its current structuring of the class in the 2022 season.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] These changes split the GT Daytona class into GTD and GTD PRO.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Both GTD classes use identical cars built to the FIA GT3 technical regulations.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The only difference is that GTD requires one amateur driver (with an FIA silver or bronze rating) while driver selection is open in GTD PRO.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Porsche has the most overall victories of any manufacturer with 23, scored by various models, including the road-based 911, 935, and 996.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] Porsche also won a record 11 consecutive races from 1977 to 1987 and won 18 out of 23 races from 1968 to 1991.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] The German carmaker also claimed to earn back-to-back wins overall in both the 2024 and 2025 races.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] In addition to their 21 wins as both car and engine manufacturer, Porsche has four wins solely as an engine manufacturer, in 1984, and 1995, and two in the Daytona Prototype era, in 2009 and 2010.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-daytona] General Motors has 10 wins between its Oldsmobile, Pontiac, Chevrolet, and Cadillac brands.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The **24 Hours of Le Mans** (French: ***24 Heures du Mans***; French pronunciation: [vɛ̃t.katʁ‿œʁ dy mɑ̃]) is an endurance sports car race held annually near the city of Le Mans, France.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] First run in 1923, it is the oldest active endurance racing event in the world and is widely considered one of the world's most prestigious races.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is part of two informal "Triple Crown" series: the Triple Crown of Motorsport (with the F1 Monaco Grand Prix and the Indianapolis 500) and the Triple Crown of endurance racing (with the Florida-based 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Unlike fixed-distance races whose winner is determined by minimum time, the 24 Hours of Le Mans is won by the car that covers the greatest distance in 24 hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The cars on this track are able to achieve speeds of 366 km/h (227 mph), and reached 407 km/h (253 mph) on the main straight in 1988 – instigating the addition of more chicanes to the track to reduce speed reached.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Racing teams must balance the demands of speed with the cars' ability to run for 24 hours without mechanical failure.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is organized by the Automobile Club de l'Ouest (ACO).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is held on the Circuit de la Sarthe, composed of closed public roads and dedicated sections of a racing track.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was often part of the World Sportscar Championship from 1953 until that series' final season in 1992.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, it was a part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2012, the race has been a part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A 10-hour American version of the race, called Petit Le Mans, has been held annually since 1998.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most recent running of the event, the 94th 24 Heures du Mans, ran from 13 to 14 June 2026.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Launched when Grand Prix motor racing was the dominant form of motorsport throughout Europe, Le Mans was designed to present a different test.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Instead of focusing on the ability of a car company to build the fastest machines, the 24 Hours of Le Mans would concentrate on the ability of manufacturers to build sporty yet reliable cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This encouraged innovation in producing reliable and fuel-efficient vehicles, because endurance racing requires cars that last and spend as little time in the pits as possible.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, the layout of the track required cars with better aerodynamics and stability at high speeds.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While this was shared with Grand Prix racing, few tracks in Europe had straights of a length comparable to the *Ligne droite des Hunaudières*, often referred to as Mulsanne Straight after the village it leads to.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The oil crisis in the early 1970s led organizers to adopt a fuel economy formula known as Group C that limited the amount of fuel each car was allowed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it was later abandoned, fuel economy remains important as new fuel sources reduce the time spent during pit stops.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such technological innovations have had a trickle-down effect and can be incorporated into consumer cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has also led to faster and more exotic supercars as manufacturers seek to develop faster road cars in order to develop them into even faster GT cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2000s, hybrid systems (flywheel, super-capacitor, battery coupled with both petrol and diesel) have been championed in the Le Mans prototype category as rules have been changed to their benefit and to further push efficiency.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is held in mid-June, near the summer solstice, meaning the shortest night and very hot conditions for drivers, particularly in closed vehicles with poor ventilation.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race begins in mid-afternoon and finishes the following day at the same hour the race started the previous day.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2025 race attracted 332,000 spectators.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Modern competitors often cover well over 5,000 km (3,110 mi).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The record is 2010's 5,410 km (3,360 mi), more than six times the length of the Indianapolis 500 (500 mi or 805 km), or about 18 times longer than a Formula One *Grand Prix*.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers and their teams strive for speed and avoiding mechanical damage, as well as managing the cars' consumables – primarily fuel, tires, and braking materials.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It also tests endurance, with drivers frequently racing for over two hours before a relief driver can take over during a pit stop while eating and resting.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Current regulations mandate that three drivers share each competing vehicle, with individual limits of driving no more than 4 hours in a 6-hour period, and no more than 14 hours total.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Competing teams race in groups called "classes", or cars of similar specification, while competing simultaneously for outright placing amongst all classes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally, the race showcased cars as they were sold to the general public, then called "Sports Cars", in contrast with the specialised racing cars used in Grand Prix motor racing.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over time, the competing vehicles evolved away from their publicly available road car roots.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These are further broken down into: Hypercar (LMH or LMDh), LMP2 and LMGT3 (GT cars).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was part of the World Sportscar Championship every year from its inception in 1953 until its demise in 1992, except during the 1956, 1975–1979 and 1989–1990 seasons.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race was part of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, and since 2012 it has been part of the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, winning Le Mans is often considered to be more important than winning the championship itself.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race is also known as a leg of the informal Triple Crown of Motorsport which links Formula One, IndyCar, and sports car racing to represent a career achievement for drivers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Additionally, it is seen as a leg of the Triple Crown of endurance racing, which links the three largest sports car races together, with the 24 Hours of Daytona and 12 Hours of Sebring forming the other legs.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1998, an endurance race called "Petit Le Mans" has been held every year as a 10-hour American version of the Le Mans 24 Hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] From 1999 to 2013, Petit Le Mans was part of the American Le Mans Series along with the 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, the IMSA SportsCar Championship (a merger of ALMS and the Rolex Sports Car Series) has held all four major American endurance classics, which teams can use to prepare for racing at Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Each car was required to have at least two seats.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, recently cars only need to have space to accommodate a second seat in the cockpit rather than the seat itself.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Two doors are allowed; open-cockpit cars do not require doors.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2014, all cars in the premier LMP1 category must have a roof for safety; open-cockpit cars are only permitted in the slightly slower LMP2 category.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2017, all prototype cars—Hypercar or LMP2—must have closed cockpits.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although all cars compete at the same time, as of 2021, there are separate classes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A prize is awarded to the winner of each class and the overall winner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The number of classes has varied over the years, but there are now three: Hypercar, LMP2, and LMGT3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Successor to the Le Mans Prototype 1 (LMP1) is the custom-built Hypercar (LMH or LMDh) class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It is the top class and debuted in 2021.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new technical regulations are intended to prevent cost escalations while enabling greater variety in technical approaches and car aesthetics.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is followed by the LMP2 class where teams are obliged to run one of four approved chassis – ORECA, Ligier, Dallara, or Multimatic/Riley – mated with a standard 4.2-litre Gibson V8 engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] ORECA is the most commonly used LMP2 chassis.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] LMP1 teams are not subjected to chassis and engine restrictions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Their extra power, lower weight, and more complex aerodynamics result in much quicker lap times; LMP1 cars also may use hybrid technology.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The next class is LMGT3, which are similar to production-based sports cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Concept cars intended to test new automotive technologies may participate in the race under the "Garage 56" banner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Such entries are classified in the race results, though are not expected to be competitive as their sole focus is to demonstrate experimental features.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, there were no rules on the number of car drivers or how long they could drive.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although almost all teams used two drivers in the early decades, some Le Mans drivers such as Pierre Levegh and Eddie Hall attempted to run the race solo, hoping to save time by not having to change drivers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until the 1980s, there were teams in which only two drivers competed, but by the end of the decade, the rules were changed to stipulate that at least three drivers must drive each car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the 1990s, due to the speeds of the cars and the strain it puts on drivers, additional rules to reduce driver fatigue mandated that drivers could not drive for over 240 minutes (over 4 hours) and that no one driver could run for over 840 minutes (14 hours) total.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With careful management of driver stints, this makes it possible to complete the race with only two drivers (as Jeroen Bleekemolen and Cooper MacNeil did in 2014), although the vast majority of teams still continue to use three drivers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, the driving time rules were further changed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] If necessary, officials may require a drive time limit of 80 minutes of consecutive time behind the wheel and a minimum 30-minute rest break.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rule applies only if the air temperature is at least 32 °C (89.6 °F).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it has been a part of the World Sportscar Championship for most of its existence, the race has had different regulations for safety and competition reasons partly due to its length.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For many decades, cars had to run at least an hour into the race before they could refill fluids for the car, such as oil or coolant, except for fuel.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was an attempt by the ACO to help increase efficiency and reliability.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those who could not last the first hour without replacing lost fluids risked disqualification.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another rule unique to Le Mans is that cars must be switched off while refueling in the pits.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Not only is this safer and less of a fire hazard, but it is also another test of reliability, demanding a guaranteed ability to restart many times under race conditions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another element of this rule is that mechanics are not allowed to work on the car while it is being refuelled (other than helping a driver in or out of the car), which has led teams to adapt innovative ways to decrease the time of these lengthy pit stops.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Drivers can get out of the car and be replaced by another driver during refuelling.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Those rules are also applied in the FIA World Endurance Championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] There are various long-standing traditions at Le Mans, including the waving of the French tricolor to start the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is usually preceded by a fly-over featuring jets trailing blue, white, and red smoke.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A similar flag tradition is track marshals waving safety flags during the race's final lap, congratulating the winners and other finishers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans was the venue for the first televised instance of a winning driver celebrating by spraying champagne instead of drinking it.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When Dan Gurney won the 1967 race with co-driver A.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt, the two drivers mounted the victory podium, and Gurney was handed a magnum of champagne.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Looking down, he saw Ford CEO Henry Ford II, team owner Carroll Shelby and their wives, as well as several journalists who had predicted disaster for the high-profile duo.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney shook the bottle and sprayed everyone nearby.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Gurney autographed and gave the bottle of champagne to *Life* photographer Flip Schulke, who used it as a lamp for years before returning it to Gurney.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race has been cancelled ten times: in 1936 (a labour strike during the Great Depression) and between 1940 and 1948 (World War II).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race usually takes place on the second weekend of June, with qualifying and practice taking place on the Wednesday and Thursday before the race, following a car inspection on Monday and Tuesday.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Currently, these sessions are held in the evening, with two separate two-hour sessions held each night.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Friday serves as a day of rest, and a parade of all the drivers through Le Mans is held.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Test days held at the end of April or beginning of May served as a pre-qualification weeding out the slowest cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, in 2005 the exorbitant cost of transporting cars to and from Le Mans led organizers to move the test day to the first weekend of June.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Pre-qualification was eliminated in 2000, meaning that all competitors invited to the test would be allowed into the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2001 the Le Mans Legend races have mostly been part of the schedule, usually running exhibition races during qualifying days, a few hours prior to the sessions for the Le Mans entrants.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since its inception, the race has usually started at 4:00 p.m. local time (Central European Summer Time, UTC + 02:00) on Saturday.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, the car that covered the greatest distance from its starting position was the winner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This is known to have caught out the Ford team in 1966.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a dominant 1–2 lead, the two cars slowed to allow for a photo opportunity at the finish line, with Ken Miles slightly ahead of Bruce McLaren.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, since McLaren's car had started much farther back on the grid than Miles's, McLaren's car had covered the greatest distance over the 24 hours.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With the margin of victory determined to be eight metres, McLaren and his co-driver, Chris Amon, were declared the winners.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decision cost Miles and Denny Hulme a victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Miles had already won the other two endurance races at Sebring and Daytona.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With a win at Le Mans, he would have become the first man to win all three and the first to win them all in the same year.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The "greatest distance" rule was modified with the introduction of a rolling start in 1971.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Now, the car that completes the greatest distance as of the final lap's completion – where "greatest distance" is measured by the start/finish line for all competitors – wins.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When two cars finish the same number of laps, their finishing order is determined by the faster overall completion time.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This rule was used in the 2011 24 Hours of Le Mans to determine the race winner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The top two finishers completed 355 laps, with only 13 seconds difference between them.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although "greatest distance run" determines the provisional order of finishers, additional requirements must be met for a car to be classified.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All classification requirements hold except in exceptional circumstances, as determined by the race stewards.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race traditionally began with what became known as the *Le Mans start*, in which cars were lined up along the length of the pits.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Until 1962, cars lined up by engine capacity.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 1963, qualifying times determined the lineup.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starting drivers stood on the opposite side of the front stretch.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] When the French flag dropped to signify the start, the drivers ran across the track, entered and started their cars without assistance, and drove away.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This became a safety issue in the late 1960s when some drivers ignored their safety harnesses, then a recent invention.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to drivers running the first few laps either improperly harnessed due to attempting to do it while driving or sometimes not even harnessed at all, leading to several deaths when cars were involved in accidents due to the bunched field at the start.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This starting method inspired Porsche to locate the ignition key switch to the left of the steering wheel.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In a left-hand drive car, this allowed the driver to use his left hand to start the engine and his right hand to put the transmission into gear, which in turn shaves off a few tenths of a second.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Stirling Moss developed another method for speeding up the start.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His car was waiting with first gear already engaged.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] He switched the starter on when he jumped in without depressing the clutch.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The starter motor immediately jerked the car forward, but the engine did not start due to low RPM.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After a few seconds of motion, he pushed the clutch down, allowing the engine to speed up and start while the car was moving.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Feeling the Le Mans Start was unsafe, in the 1969 race, Jacky Ickx opposed it by walking across the track while his competitors ran.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although he was nearly hit by a faster competitor's car while walking, Ickx took the time to fasten his safety belts before pulling away.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Privateer John Woolfe died in an accident on the first lap of that race; Ickx won.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The traditional Le Mans start was changed for 1970.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars were still lined up along the pit wall, but the drivers were already inside and strapped in.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the dropping of the French tricolor, the drivers started their engines and drove away.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1971, a rolling start (sometimes known as an *Indianapolis start*) begins the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While the cars do still start out lined up against the pit wall, when the green flag is waved the cars pull away one by one to begin a formation lap behind the safety car; when that car returns to the pit lane, the starter waves the French flag to start the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit on which the 24 Hours of Le Mans is run is named the Circuit de la Sarthe, after the department that Le Mans is within.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] It consists of both permanent track and public roads temporarily closed for the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 1923, the track has been extensively modified, mostly for safety reasons, and now is 13.626 km (8.467 mi) in length.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although it initially entered the town of Le Mans, the track was cut short to better protect spectators.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This led to the creation of the Dunlop Curve and Tertre Rouge corners before rejoining the old circuit on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another major change was on the Mulsanne itself in 1990 when the FIA decreed that it would no longer sanction any circuit that had a straight longer than 2 km (1.2 mi).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] To comply with this, two chicanes were added to the 6-kilometre-long (3.7 mi) straight, dividing it into three pieces about 2 km each.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The addition of the chicanes was further influenced by the fact that the speed of Welter Racing's WM P88, driven by French driver Roger Dorchy, had been timed at 407 km/h (253 mph) during the 1988 race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was the record speed before the addition of the chicanes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to the shorter length of the straights, the speed record at Le Mans now, after the introduction of the chicanes, is 366 km/h (227 mph).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Typically race cars achieve top speed of just under 320 km/h (200 mph) at the current track (with chicanes).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The public sections of the track differ from the permanent circuit, especially in comparison with the Bugatti Circuit which is inside the Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Due to heavy traffic, the public roads are not as smooth or well kept.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They also offer less grip because of the lack of soft-tyre rubber laid down from racing cars, though this only affects the first few laps of the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The roads are closed only within a few hours of the practice sessions and the race before being opened again almost as soon as the race is finished.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Workers have to assemble and dismantle safety barriers every year for the public sections.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 24 Hours of Le Mans was first run on 26 and 27 May 1923, through public roads around Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally planned to be a three-year event, as part of the Rudge-Whitworth Triennial Cup, with a winner being declared by the car which could go the farthest distance over three consecutive 24-hour races, this idea was abandoned in 1928.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Overall winners were declared for every year depending on who covered the furthest distance by the time 24 hours were up.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The early races were dominated by French, British, and Italian drivers, teams, and cars, with Bugatti, Bentley, and Alfa Romeo being the top brands.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Innovations in car design began appearing at the track in the late 1930s, with Bugatti and Alfa Romeo running highly aerodynamic bodywork to run down the Mulsanne Straight at faster speeds.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The race was cancelled in 1936 due to general strikes in France, and the outbreak of World War II in 1939 resulted in a ten-year hiatus.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the reconstruction of circuit facilities, the race was resumed in 1949 with renewed interest from major automobile manufacturers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 1949 was also Ferrari's first victory, the 166MM of Luigi Chinetti and Peter Mitchell-Thomson.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After the formation of the World Sportscar Championship in 1953, of which Le Mans was a part, Ferrari, Aston Martin, Mercedes-Benz, Jaguar and many others began sending multiple cars backed by their respective factories to compete for overall wins against their competitors.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This competitiveness sometimes resulted in tragedy, as in the 1955 Le Mans disaster during the 1955 race in which Pierre Levegh's car crashed into a crowd of spectators, killing more than 80 people.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The incident led to the widespread introduction of safety measures, not only at the circuit but elsewhere in the motorsport world.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The entire pit complex was razed and rebuilt further back following the accident, allowing the pit straight to be widened.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, there was still no barrier between the track and the pit lane.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Safety standards improved, but the cars got faster.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The move from open-cockpit roadsters to closed-cockpit coupés resulted in speeds of over 320 km/h (200 mph) on the Mulsanne.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford entered the picture with the GT40, finally ending Ferrari's dominance with four straight wins (1966–1969) before the 1960s ended and the cars and the race changed substantially.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In those years racing took a turn towards more extreme speeds and automotive designs.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This contributed to the replacement of the typical standing *Le Mans start* with a rolling *Indianapolis start*.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Purpose-built sportscars became the norm, with the traditional production-based cars now racing in lower classes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche was dominant throughout the decade with their 917, 935, and 936 models.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] French manufacturers Matra-Simca and Renault also gained success, with the first victories for the nation since the 1950 race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Notably, 1978 saw the first win of a turbocharged engine with the Renault Alpine A443.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The decade is also remembered for strong performances from many privateer constructors, with two scoring the only victories for a privateer in the decade.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] John Wyer's Mirage won in 1975, while Jean Rondeau's self-titled chassis took 1980.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The rest of the 1980s was known for the dominance by Porsche under the new Group C race car formula that encouraged fuel efficiency.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Originally running the effective 956, it was later replaced by the 962.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Both chassis were affordable enough for privateers to purchase them en masse, leading to the two model types winning six years in a row.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Jaguar and Mercedes-Benz returned to sports car racing, with Jaguar being the first to break Porsche's dominance with victories in 1988 and 1990 (with the XJR-9 and Jaguar XJR-12 respectively).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mercedes-Benz won in 1989, with what was seen as the latest incarnation of the elegant "Silver Arrows", the Sauber C9, while an influx of Japanese manufacturer interest saw prototypes from Nissan and Toyota.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In qualifying for the 1988 race, a WM Peugeot – built for speed, not meant to (and it did not) endure 24 hours – set the never surpassed speed trap record of 407 km/h (253 mph) in the *Ligne Droite des Hunaudières*, famous for its 6 km (3.7 mi) long straight.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda would be the first Japanese manufacturer to succeed, with their unique rotary-powered 787B winning in 1991.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1992 and 1993, Peugeot dominated the race with its Peugeot 905 as the Group C formula and World Sportscar Championship were fading in participation.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The circuit would also undergo one of its most notable changes in 1990, when the 5 km long Mulsanne was modified to include two chicanes in order to stop speeds of more than 400 km/h (250 mph) from being reached again.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This began the ACO's trend to slow the cars on various portions of the track.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, speeds over 320 km/h (200 mph) are still regularly reached at various points on a lap.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Following the demise of the World Sportscar Championship, Le Mans saw a resurgence of production-based grand tourer cars.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Thanks to a loophole in the rules, Porsche succeeded in convincing the ACO that a Dauer 962 Le Mans supercar was a production car, allowing Porsche to race their Porsche 962 for one final time, dominating the field.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although the ACO attempted to close the loophole for 1995, newcomer McLaren would win the race in their supercar's first appearance thanks to the reliability of the BMW V12 powered F1 GTR, beating faster yet more trouble-prone prototypes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The trend would continue through the 1990s as more exotic supercars were built in order to skirt the ACO's rules regarding production-based race cars, leading to Porsche, Mercedes-Benz, Toyota, Nissan, Panoz, and Lotus entering the GT categories.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This culminated in the 1999 event, in which these GT cars were faced with the Le Mans Prototypes of BMW, Audi, Toyota and Ferrari.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] BMW would survive with the victory, their first and only overall Le Mans win to date.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Mercedes left sportscar racing indefinitely following three catastrophic though non-fatal crashes stemming from severe aerodynamic flaws with their CLR.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This strong manufacturer influence led the ACO to lend the Le Mans name to a sports car series in the United States in 1999, known as the American Le Mans Series, which ran until the end of the 2013 season after which it merged with Grand-Am to form the United SportsCar Championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Many major automobile manufacturers withdrew from sports car racing after 1999 due to the high cost.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Only Cadillac and Audi remained, and Audi easily dominated with the R8.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cadillac pulled out three years later, and attempts by Panoz, Chrysler, and MG to beat Audi all fell short.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After three victories in a row, Audi provided engine, team staff, and drivers to Bentley, a corporate partner, which had returned in 2001.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2003, the factory Bentley Speed 8s beat privateer Audis.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Chevrolet Corvette Racing Team and their C5-R won several times in the GTS class, finishing 1st and 2nd in 2001, 2002, and 2004.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] They finished 2nd and 3rd in 2003 behind Ferrari.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the end of 2005, after five overall victories for the R8, and six to its V8 turbo engine, Audi took on a new challenge by introducing a diesel engined prototype known as the R10 TDI.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although not the first diesel to race, it was the first to win at Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This era saw other alternative fuel sources used, including bio-ethanol.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At the same time, Peugeot decided to follow Audi's lead and pursue a diesel entry in 2007 with their 908 HDi FAP.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 2008 race between the Audi R10 TDI and the Peugeot 908 HDi FAP, the Audi won by a margin of fewer than 10 minutes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For the 2009 24 Hours of Le Mans, Peugeot introduced a new energy-recovery system similar to the KERS used in Formula One.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aston Martin entered the LMP1 category, but still raced in GT1 with private teams.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi returned with the new R15 TDI, but Peugeot prevailed in its first overall win since 1993.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2010 running reaffirmed the race as a test of endurance and reliability.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Peugeot chose overall speed in adjusting their cars and engines to adhere to the 2010 regulations, while Audi chose reliability.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] All four Peugeots had retired at the end of the race, three due to engine failure, while Audi finished 1–2–3.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2011 and 2012 races were marred by a series of accidents.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the Audi driven by Allan McNish crashed heavily in the first hour, barrel rolling into a tire wall shortly after the Dunlop Bridge.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] At night, the defending race-winning Audi driven by Mike Rockenfeller crashed similarly between the Mulsanne and Indianapolis corners.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Neither driver was seriously injured, nor were any spectators.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The third Audi entry was driven by Marcel Fässler, André Lotterer, and Benoît Tréluyer won the race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 race saw two factory Toyotas replace Peugeot, which had withdrawn earlier, but one flipped at Mulsanne Corner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Driver Anthony Davidson suffered two broken vertebrae but could exit the car himself.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Shortly after sunset, the other Toyota retired with mechanical difficulties, leading to another Audi victory.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2011, the race became the premier round of the Intercontinental Le Mans Cup, attempting to make a world championship for endurance racing again.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012, the race became the centerpiece of the FIA World Endurance Championship, the successor to the ILMC.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The 2012 event was the first time the race was won by a hybrid electric vehicle, which was the Audi R18 e-tron quattro.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Regulations were changed for 2014, notably with a requirement that all LMP1 cars must be closed-cockpit, some changes to the hybrid system, and the introduction of the slow zone system.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche returned to Le Mans in 2014 with a new factory LMP1 program, and Nissan returned to run an LMP1 program in 2015.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi withdrew from racing at the 24 Hours of Le Mans in 2016 and Nissan after only one attempt in 2015.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Porsche won the race in 2015, 2016, and 2017 with its hybrid 919, and remains the most successful manufacturer at Le Mans, with 19 overall victories.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2017, changes were made to the LMP2 regulations on cockpit and chassis, meaning all prototype cars must be closed-cockpit.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota won their first Le Mans with Fernando Alonso, Sébastien Buemi and Kazuki Nakajima driving.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2020 also saw the race held behind closed doors for the first time due to the COVID-19 pandemic.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the introduction of the Hypercar class, a class that allows for Le Mans Hypercars and from 2023 onwards also LMDh cars to participate.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2021 saw the race postponed once again, this time until August.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] For 2021 and 2022, non-hybrid LMP1 cars were allowed to participate as "grandfathered" LMP1 cars, although only Alpine would make use of this.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Other entries in the hypercar class were Toyota and privateer team Glickenhaus.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The new Hypercar regulations allowed manufacturers more freedom with the design, leading to cars such as the wingless Peugeot 9X8 entering in 2022, with other unique designs expected to be added.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The LMP2 regulations were extended to 2027 with the next generation LMP2 cars to be introduced in 2028.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] 2028 will likely also see the introduction of hydrogen powered prototypes.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The former LMGTE class was also replaced by LMGT3 in 2024.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Le Mans has seen many innovations in automotive design to counteract the circuit's difficulties.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] These have either been dictated by rules or have been attempts by manufacturers to outwit the competition.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Some innovations were incorporated into the everyday automobile.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] One of the keys to Le Mans is top speed due to the long straights that dominate the circuit.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This has meant cars have attempted to achieve the maximum speeds possible instead of relying on downforce for the turns.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] While early competitors' cars were street cars with their bodywork removed to reduce weight, innovators like Bugatti developed cars that saw the beginnings of aerodynamics.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Nicknamed *tanks* due to their similarity to military tanks in World War I, these cars used simple curves to cover all the car's mechanical elements and increase top speed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Once Le Mans returned after World War II, most manufacturers would adopt closed bodies streamlined for better aerodynamics.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A notable example of the changes brought about by aerodynamics are the 1950 entries by Briggs Cunningham.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cunningham entered two 1950 Cadillac Coupe de Villes, one nearly stock and the other completely rebodied in a streamlined aluminum shape developed by Grumman Aircraft Engineering Corporation that looked so unusual that it was nicknamed "Le Monstre" by the French press.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The smoothing of body shapes and fairing-in of various parts of the machine brought about by the continual search for reduction of aerodynamic drag led to a separation from Grand Prix cars, which rarely had large bodywork.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] As the years went on, bodywork became all-enveloping, while at the same time lighter.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The larger bodywork with spoilers was able to provide more downforce for the turns without increasing the drag, allowing cars to maintain high speeds.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Extended bodywork would usually concentrate on the car's rear, usually being termed *long tail*.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The bodywork also began to cover the cockpit for less drag.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, open cockpits would come and go over the years as rules varied.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Aerodynamics reached its peak in 1989 before the Mulsanne Straight was modified.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] During the 1988 race, the crew of a Peugeot powered WM prototype taped over the engine openings, allowing Roger Dorchy to set a recorded speed of 407 km/h (253 mph) down the Mulsanne.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, the car was almost undrivable elsewhere on the circuit.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The engine was soon destroyed from a lack of cooling.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, for the 1989 event, the Mercedes-Benz C9 reached 400 km/h (249 mph) under qualifying conditions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] A wide variety of engines have competed at Le Mans in attempts to achieve greater speed and fuel economy and to spend less time in the pits.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Engine sizes have also varied greatly, with the smallest engines being a mere 569 cc (Simca Cinq) and the largest upwards of 8,000 cc (SRT Viper GTS-R).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Supercharging was an early innovation for increasing output, first being raced in 1929, while turbocharging first appeared in 1974.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The first entry without a piston engine came in 1963, when Rover partnered with British Racing Motors to run a gas turbine car with mixed success, an effort they repeated in 1965.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The American Howmet Corporation attempted to employ a turbine in 1968 with even less success: although the engines offered great power, they were hot and not fuel-efficient.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Another non-piston engine that appeared was the Wankel engine, otherwise known as the rotary engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Used exclusively (in automotive applications) by Mazda since its introduction in 1970, the compact rotary engine suffered from fuel economy problems, yet eventually achieved the success that the turbines had not.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After many years of development, Mazda finally became the only winner of the race not to have a piston-powered engine, as it took the 1991 event with the 787B.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative fuel sources have also played a part in more normal engine designs, with the first non-gasoline car appearing in 1949.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The Delettrez Special was powered by a diesel engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, a second diesel appeared in the form of the M.A.P. the following year.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Although diesel was used on several occasions, it was not until 2006 that a prominent manufacturer, Audi, invested in diesel; the company's R10 TDI was a success.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ethanol fuel appeared in 1980 in a modified Porsche 911, leading to a class win.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Alternative biological fuel sources returned again in 2004 with Team Nasamax's DM139-Judd.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2008, biofuels (10% ethanol for petrol engines and biodiesel for diesel engines) were allowed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi was the first to use next-generation 10% BTL biodiesel developed by Shell and manufactured from biomass.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Beginning in 2009, new regulations allowed hybrid vehicles with either KERS or TERS (Kinetic/Thermal Energy Recovery System) setups.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, only electrical (i.e., battery) energy storage was allowed, ruling out flywheel-based energy recovery.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Cars with KERS were allowed to race in 2009 under specific classification rules.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2010, they have competed for points and the championship.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2012 the first KERS-equipped car won; the Audi R18 e-tron with a flywheel hybrid system by Williams Hybrid Power activated and drove the front wheels.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This was only allowed in certain zones after the car had accelerated to at least 120 km/h to cancel out the acceleration advantage that all-wheel-drive cars could gain out of corners.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the same year, Toyota also started with a hybrid car, the TS030, which used KERS to power its rear wheels, meaning its usage was not restricted.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2025, the Automobile Club de l’Ouest is planning to introduce a hydrogen-electric prototype class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] This class will be a one-design class with a chassis provided by Red Bull Advanced Technologies-Oreca and a powertrain supplied by GreenGT.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The development of the hydrogen fuel cells powering the cars will be left to the teams themselves.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] According to the ACO's president Pierre Fillon, there is also a possibility of the cars being powered by a hydrogen combustion engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The performance of the class is expected to be competitive with the top Hypercar class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Toyota unveiled new GR LH2 prototype for Gazoo Racing Europe.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] With increased speeds around the track, brakes become a key issue for teams attempting to safely bring their cars down to a slow enough speed to make the Mulsanne Corner turn.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Disc brakes were first seen in 1953 when the Jaguar C-Type raced at Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 1955 the Mercedes-Benz 300 SLR introduced the air brake using a large opening hood on the rear of the car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Ford used a quick change brake rotor in 1966 to achieve their first victory at Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In the 1980s, anti-lock braking systems became standard on most Group C cars as a safety measure, making it less likely that cars lose control at high speeds.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] By the late 1990s, reinforced carbon-carbon brakes were adopted for better stopping power.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Over the years, many manufacturers have managed to take the overall win, while even more have taken class wins.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] The most successful marque in the history of the race is Porsche, which has taken nineteen overall victories, including seven in a row from 1981 to 1987 and 107 class victories.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi is next with thirteen wins, and Ferrari follows with eleven, also including six in a row from 1960 to 1965.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Since 2000 Audi has dominated the event, winning 13 times in 15 years of participation.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Audi and Team Joest have had two hat-tricks, the first being in 2000, 2001, and 2002.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In contrast, Toyota won five races in a row and Bentley, Alfa Romeo, and Ford all won four races in a row, with Bentley recording two additional victories in other years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] In 2018, Toyota became only the second Japanese marque to win, following Mazda in 1991.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Mazda is also the only company to win with a rotary engine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] After Porsche's total of 107 class victories, Ferrari has 37, and Aston Martin, Audi, and Chevrolet each have 14.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three drivers stand apart for their number of victories.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Initially, Jacky Ickx held the record at six, scoring victories between 1969 and 1982, earning him honorary citizenship to the town of Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] His frequent racing partner, Derek Bell, trailing by a single win, with five.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] However, Tom Kristensen has beaten this record with nine wins between 1997 and 2013, including six in a row.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Three-time winner Woolf Barnato (1928 to 1930), Tazio Nuvolari (1933), Luis Fontés (1935), American racing legend A.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Foyt (1967), Nico Hülkenberg (2015), and Fernando Alonso (2018–2019) are the only drivers to have won every Le Mans in which they participated.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Henri Pescarolo won the race four times, and holds the record for the most Le Mans appearances at 33.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Japan's Yojiro Terada was active as a driver until 2008, and holds the record for the most Le Mans starts without an overall win.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Claude Ballot-Léna holds the most class victories other than Kristensen with seven wins in GT class cars between 1970 and 1986.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p01] Graham Hill is the only driver to win the so-called *Triple Crown of Motorsport*, winning the Indianapolis 500 (1966), Monaco Grand Prix (1963, 1964, 1965, 1968, 1969), and the 24 Hours of Le Mans (1972).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Le Mans has seen many fatal accidents due partly to the very high-speed nature of all variants of the track throughout history.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The largest one was in 1955 when at least 81 spectators (exact number unknown, many sources estimate 83) and driver Pierre Levegh were killed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the wake of the disaster, many races were cancelled, including the Grand Prix races in Germany, Spain, France and Switzerland (the latter as a part of a blanket ban on motorsport round-track races that was maintained until 2022).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The accident led to safety regulations in all motorsports for both driver and spectator protection.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Almost all decades in which Le Mans has been run have seen many horrific accidents, such as in 1972 when Jo Bonnier was catapulted into a forest surrounding the circuit after hitting a privately entered Ferrari near the Indianapolis section; Bonnier was killed instantly.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1980s was a decade where some of the race's worst-ever accidents occurred.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Armco barriers had been installed along the straight in 1969, there were still no chicanes on the Mulsanne Straight.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] It was here that almost all of the worst accidents occurred during that time.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1981, Belgian Thierry Boutsen crashed on the Mulsanne Straight in his WM-Peugeot, killing a marshal.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the same race, Frenchman Jean-Louis Lafosse was also killed on the Mulsanne Straight when his Rondeau suffered a suspension failure, steered very suddenly to the right, and slammed into the Armco barrier on the driver's side at extreme speeds.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 1984 race saw British privateer John Sheldon crashing at more than 320 km/h (200 mph) at the Mulsanne Kink; his Aston Martin V8 powered Nimrod tore through the Armco barriers into the trees.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The resulting explosion was so violent that the woods next to the track caught fire.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Although Sheldon survived with severe burns, a track marshal was killed; two others were also severely injured.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Sheldon's teammate, American Drake Olson in the second Nimrod-Aston Martin, who was following him down the straight, crashed heavily after running over Sheldon's bodywork; he went into severe shock but survived with minor injuries.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The field was under the safety car for over an hour while the crash site was cleared, and the destroyed Armco barriers were replaced.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, a similar accident befell Briton Dudley Wood in a Porsche 962 during practice.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The impact of the car against the Armco, considering Wood was doing more than 370 km/h (230 mph), was so hard that it cracked the engine block.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1985, John Nielsen flipped his Sauber-Mercedes while going over the Mulsanne hump at more than 350 km/h (220 mph).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The car landed on its roof and was destroyed, but Nielsen escaped without injury.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1986, Jo Gartner drove a Porsche 962C into the Mulsanne barriers and was killed instantly after the car rolled multiple times, vaulted some Armco barriers, and knocked down a telegraph pole.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Moreover, in 1987, American Price Cobb crashed a works Porsche 962C after slipping on oil during Wednesday practice.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The fuel tank exploded and the car burned to the ground, but Cobb escaped without injury.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Gartner's fatal accident remained the most recent death in the race until Allan Simonsen's crash in 2013.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, there was one fatality during a practice session in 1997 (Sebastien Enjolras).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 1999, the Mercedes-Benz CLRs suffered from aerodynamic instability leading to cars getting airborne and flipping backwards, no less than three times.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] After initially happening on Thursday to the #4 car, Mercedes rebuilt the chassis on Friday and claimed to have solved the problem, only for it to occur again at warmup on Saturday.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Mark Webber was the unlucky driver whose car flipped on both occasions.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The last and most damaging accident occurred during the race itself when Peter Dumbreck's CLR #5 became airborne, flying over the safety fencing and landing in the woods several metres away.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] No drivers were severely hurt in any of the three accidents.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, Mercedes-Benz withdrew its remaining entry and ended its entire sportscar programme to focus on F1 and the upcoming new DTM.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2011, two horrific accidents occurred to two of the three factory Audis in the LMP1 class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 3 car driven by Allan McNish collided with one of the Ferrari GT cars, resulting in McNish's car smashing into the tyre wall and being thrown into the air at the Dunlop chicanes, resulting in pieces of bodywork flying over and nearly hitting many photographers on the other side of the barrier.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the eleventh hour of the race, another accident occurred to the No.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] 1 car driven by Mike Rockenfeller when he had contact with another Ferrari GT car.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the runup to Indianapolis corner, Rockenfeller's Audi was sent into the outside barrier at over 270 km/h (170 mph).
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Only the main cockpit safety cell of the car remained, along with major damage being done to the barriers that needed to be repaired before the race was resumed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Audi had switched to a closed-cockpit car starting in 2011, a decision credited for the fact that neither driver was injured.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The 2014 regulations required all cars to be closed-cockpit due to the 2011 accident.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2012, Anthony Davidson, driving for the returning Toyota team in a Toyota TS030 Hybrid, collided with a Ferrari 458 GT2 of Piergiuseppe Perazzini, and became airborne before crashing into the tyre barrier of the Mulsanne Corner at high speed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The Ferrari also ended up in the barrier, flipping and coming to a halt on its roof.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2013, Allan Simonsen died after crashing into the barriers at Tertre Rouge.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] When the car collided with the guard rail, a mature tree had been touching the barrier, thereby preventing the guard rail from performing its safety function.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Motors TV covered the Le Mans 24 Hours in its entirety in 2006 and 2007, including coverage of the scrutineering, qualifying, driver parade, warmup, and race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the United States, FOX owned SPEED Channel, followed by Fox Sports 1 and Fox Sports 2 aired complete race coverage live either on-air or online through a combination of coverage from the French host broadcaster and its own pit reporting crew for several years.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A United States television deal was not done for the 2018–19 WEC Super Season because of a renegotiation of its European contract.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In 2008, Eurosport secured a multi-year deal to show the entire race, including the qualifying and the motorcycle race.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Every hour of the 2008 race was broadcast in segments on the main channel and Eurosport 2.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] However, a couple of hours were missed in recent years due to scheduling clashes with other sporting events.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In addition, Eurosport provided live streaming on its website to subscribers.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2009, Eurosport and Eurosport 2 have covered all the action, and beginning in 2018, Eurosport gained United States broadcast rights for the World Endurance Championship for the race only on Motor Trend, a channel also owned by Eurosport's parent company.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Qualifying and practices aired on a direct-to-consumer streaming platform from Motor Trend magazine.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In Australia in 2012, Ten Sport showed the race live and in full online.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The race is also broadcast (in English) on the radio by Radio Le Mans.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Since 2001, the ACO has allowed the "Le Mans Legend" event to participate on the full Circuit de la Sarthe.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] These exhibition races involve classic cars that had previously run at Le Mans or are similar to those.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Each year, a particular era of cars may participate, with the featured era changing from year to year.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Though most drivers in this event are amateurs, some noted professional drivers have appeared to race cars they had previously run, such as Stirling Moss and Derek Bell.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Starting in 2002, the "Le Mans Classic" has been held as a biennial event on the full 13 km (8.1 mi) circuit in July.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The races take place over a full 24-hour day/night cycle, with starts on set times allowing cars from the same era to compete simultaneously.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] A team typically consists of a car in each class.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The team with the most points accumulated over five or six classes is declared the overall winner.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The classes are based on the era in which the cars would have competed.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] The exact class requirements are re-evaluated for every event since the age for the youngest entries is shifted by two years for each event.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] In the first event, five classes ran more short races; later events have featured six classes running fewer but longer races.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] Drivers are required to have an FIA International Competition license.
[src:bmw/24-hours-of-le-mans-p02] This event also includes a large Concours d'Elegance and auction.
[src:bmw/9ff] Jan Fatthauer founded 9ff Fahrzeugtechnik GmbH in 2001 in Dortmund, Germany, as a Porsche tuning company.
[src:bmw/9ff] Fatthauer earned a degree in automotive engineering, and had worked at recognized tuners until 2001.
[src:bmw/9ff] In May 2004, 9ff achieved its first record, reaching 372 km/h (231 mph) with a 9ff T6 on the Nardo Ring race track in Nardo, Italy.
[src:bmw/9ff] The company claimed that they had the "fastest Porsche in Nardo".
[src:bmw/9ff] In December of that year, Fatthauer drove a new car, the 9ff V400, up to 388 km/h (241 mph).
[src:bmw/9ff] This car held the record for the world's fastest car until the company beat that record with the GT9 later that year.
[src:bmw/9ff] At the time, 9ff was building a wide variety of products, including some powered by alternative fuel, setting several records.
[src:bmw/9ff] In September 2006, the 9ff TRC-85 reached 380.5 km/h (236.4 mph), becoming the fastest street-legal convertible of its time.
[src:bmw/9ff] In October 2008, the 9ff CT78, based on the Porsche Cayman, won the top-speed record for cars powered by alternative fuel, with its top speed of 347 km/h (216 mph), powered by bioethanol.
[src:bmw/9ff] On April 10, 2008, the 9ff GT9 reached 407 km/h (253 mph) (confirmed with GPS), becoming the fastest street-legal car in the world.
[src:bmw/9ff] In 2009, 9ff unveiled the Speed9, the second car entirely built by 9ff.
[src:bmw/9ff] The Speed9 is a classic roadster that has a lower windshield and cleaner horizontal lines than the 1955 Porsche 356/1 500S Speedster and the 911 and 964 Speedster (1989 and 1993 respectively) that it is based on.
[src:bmw/9ff] The same year, the 9ff TR1000 became the fastest Porsche 911 in the world on the racing circuit in Papenburg, with a top speed of 391.7 km/h (243.4 mph).
[src:bmw/9ff] In early 2010, 9ff introduced the twin-turbocharged version of the Porsche GT3 and the Porsche GT3RS, through its new tuning program, the GTurbo.
[src:bmw/9ff] Two turbochargers were added to upgrade the vehicle's horsepower to 750, 850 or 1,000 hp.
[src:bmw/9ff] 9ff added new bumpers front and rear, side skirts, new quarter panels, and extra vents.
[src:bmw/9ff] With the 1,000 hp option, the car could reach 100 km/h (62 mph) in 2.9 seconds, with a top speed of 392 km/h (244 mph).
[src:bmw/9ff] The company also upgraded the direct-injection Porsche Turbo.
[src:bmw/9ff] In 2013 9ff filed for bankruptcy, along with Gumpert, Wiesmann, Artega and Lola.
[src:bmw/9ff] This has been attributed to a decline in business as Porsche drew in more customers seeking unmodified cars.
[src:bmw/9ff] A new company, 9ff Engineering GmbH, was founded in October of the same year.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] AB InBev was formed in 2008, with Belgian-Brazilian brewing company InBev's acquisition of the American company Anheuser-Busch.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV is a publicly listed company, with its primary listing on the Euronext Brussels.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] It has secondary listings on Mexico City Stock Exchange, Johannesburg Stock Exchange, and New York Stock Exchange.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] AB InBev has offices in New York City, alongside regional headquarters in São Paulo, London, St.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Louis, Mexico City, Bremen, Johannesburg, and others.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] It has approximately 630 beer brands in 150 countries.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Interbrew then acquired a number of local breweries in Belgium.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] By 1991, the second phase of targeted external growth began outside Belgium.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The first transaction in this phase took place in Hungary, followed in 1995 by the acquisition of Labatt Brewing Company (founded 1847), the largest brewer in Canada, and then in 1999 by a joint venture with Sun in Russia.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2000, Interbrew acquired Bass and Whitbread in the UK.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] They then acquired a number of German breweries: Diebels and Beck's & Co.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] (founded 1873, the maker of the world's top selling German beer) in 2001, the Gilde Group in 2002, and Spaten in 2003.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2002, Interbrew also acquired stakes in the K.K.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Brewery and the Zhujiang Brewery, strengthening its position in China.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Interbrew operated as a family-owned business until December 2000.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] At this point it organized an initial public offering, becoming a publicly owned company trading on the Euronext stock exchange (Brussels, Belgium).
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Ambev operates in 18 countries in the Americas and its products include beers such as Antarctica, Bogotá Beer Company, Brahma, Bohemia, Stella Artois and soft drinks like Guaraná Antarctica, Soda Antarctica, Sukita and the innovations H2OH! and Guarah.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The subsidiary is listed on B3, the São Paulo stock exchange, and on the New York Stock Exchange.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2004, Interbrew and AmBev merged, creating InBev.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] While its core business is beer, the company also had a strong presence in the soft drink market in Latin America.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] It employed about 86,000 people and was headquartered in Leuven, Belgium, where Anheuser-Busch InBev is based.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] InBev employed close to 89,000 people, running operations in over 30 countries across the Americas, Europe and Asia Pacific.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2006, InBev increased its share of Cerveza Quilmes, the largest beer manufacturer in Argentina, to 91%.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2007, InBev bought Lakeport Brewing Company, the largest discount brewer in Canada and realized 14.4 billion euro in revenue.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The Interbrew and AmBev merger was valued at $11.5 billion, and consolidated the top brands from Belgium, Canada, Germany and Brazil.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The merger combined the third largest brewing company in the world (Interbrew) and fifth largest (Ambev) into the world's No.1 beermaker.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Before the merger, Heineken International was in fourth place, SABMiller was in second place, and Anheuser-Busch had been the largest.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Budweiser, Beck's, Corona, and Stella Artois.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2008, InBev acquired Anheuser-Busch, creating Anheuser-Busch InBev (AB InBev), expanding on InBev's previous status as the world's largest brewer, creating one of the top five consumer products companies in the world.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Under the terms of the merger agreement, all shares of Anheuser-Busch were acquired for US$70 per share in cash, for an aggregate of US$52 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch was established in 1852 in St.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Louis, Missouri, US as *Anheuser & Co.* It is the largest brewing company in the United States and employs over 30,000 people.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] It was the world's largest brewing company based on revenue, but third in brewing volume, before the acquisition by InBev announced 13 July 2008.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The division operated 12 breweries in the United States and 17 others overseas.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch's best-known beers included brands such as Budweiser, the Busch (originally known as Busch Bavarian Beer) and Michelob families, and Natural Light and Ice.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The company also produced a number of smaller-volume and specialty beers, nonalcoholic brews like Budweiser Prohibition which made its first appearance in Canadian markets in 2016, malt liquors (King Cobra and the Hurricane family), and flavored malt beverages (e.g., Tequiza).
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch had been one of the largest theme park operators in the United States with ten parks throughout the United States.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In October 2009, AB InBev announced the sale of its Busch Entertainment theme park division to The Blackstone Group for US$2.7 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The company had been investigating a sale of Busch Entertainment since the merger with AB InBev.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2012, AB InBev bought a 51% stake of Cervecería Nacional Dominicana, a beer producer in the Dominican Republic which was the largest in the Antilles and Central America.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2013, the company bought Grupo Modelo, Mexico's leading brewer and owner of the Corona brand.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] This transaction was valued at US$20.1 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] To satisfy US anti-trust demands, on 7 June 2013 AB InBev sold its Grupo Modelo's US business, including Grupo Modelo's brand naming rights and one of the breweries in Piedras Negras in Mexico, for approx.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] US$4.75 billion to Constellation Brands, a competitor of AB Inbev in some beverage sectors.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] On 1 April 2014, AB Inbev completed the re-acquisition of the Oriental Brewery (OB), which it had sold in July 2009.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] OB is the largest brewer in South Korea.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Its *CASS* brand is the best-selling beer in South Korea.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] All beers produced by OB are brewed using rice.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In 2013, AB InBev opened its Bud Analytics Lab in Research Park, University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign, which develops data research and innovation to solve problems ranging from assortment optimization, social media, and market trends to large scale data initiatives.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The company had previously offered £38, £40, £42.15, £43.50 per share respectively, but each of these had been turned down.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] SABMiller accepted the bid in principle, but consummation of the deal required antitrust approval by regulatory agencies.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The merger (AB InBev acquisition of SABMiller), closed on 10 October 2016.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] SABMiller ceased trading on global stock markets and divested itself of its interests in the MillerCoors beer company to Molson Coors.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The new AB InBev entity is the world's largest beer company.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Estimated annual sales are US$55 billion and the company will have an estimated global market share of 28 percent, according to Euromonitor International.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] As per the agreement with the regulators, the former SABMiller sold to Molson Coors full ownership of the Miller brand portfolio outside of the U.S. and Puerto Rico for US$12 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Molson Coors also retained "the rights to all of the brands currently in the MillerCoors portfolio for the U.S. and Puerto Rico, including Redd's and import brands such as Peroni, Grolsch and Pilsner Urquell." The agreement made Molson Coors the world's third-largest brewer.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In Canada, Molson Coors regained the right to make and market Miller Genuine Draft and Miller Lite from the former SABMiller.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser Busch Company also owns a soft drinks business that has bottling contracts with PepsiCo through its subsidiary, Ambev.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In December 2016, Coca-Cola Co. bought many of the former SABMiller's Coca-Cola operations, including those in Africa.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] As part of the agreements made with regulators before Anheuser-Busch InBev was allowed to acquire SABMiller, the company sold the Peroni, Meantime and Grolsch brands to Asahi on 13 October 2016.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] After acquiring SABMiller, Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV agreed on 21 December 2016 to sell the former SABMiller Ltd. business in Poland, the Czech Republic, Slovakia, Hungary and Romania to Asahi Breweries Group Holdings, Ltd. for US$7.8 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The deal includes popular brands such as Pilsner Urquell, Tyskie, Lech, Dreher and Ursus.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In August 2017, the company announced the formation of a 50–50 joint venture with Anadolu Efes, by merging both of their operations in Russia-with the entity to be known as AB InBev-Efes.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] AB InBev owns 24 percent of Anadolu Efes from its SABMiller acquisition, with the joint venture being consolidated in Anadolu Efes books, whilst being treated as an equity investment by AB InBev.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] On 21 July 2017, Anheuser-Busch InBev continued its investment in the non-alcohol beverage sector with the purchase of energy drink company Hiball.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In December 2018, Anheuser-Busch InBev partnered with cannabis producer Tilray to begin researching cannabis infused non-alcoholic beverages with Tilray subsidiary, High Park Company.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] At the end of 2019, total liabilities amounted to US$95.5 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Net debt to normalized EBITDA decreased to 4.0×.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Goodwill reached US$128.114 billion, which compares with revenues of US$52.329 billion in 2019.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] For this deleveraging, the dividend for 2018 in EUR was cut in half compared with 2017.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] On 8 August 2023, Anheuser-Busch sold off several brands to Tilray.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] These included Blue Point Brewing Company, Breckenridge Brewery, Shock Top, Redhook Ale Brewery, Widmer Brothers Brewery, 10 Barrel Brewing Company, Square Mile Cider Company, and HiBall Energy.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In November 2023, the company began a buyback of shares-it is planned to buy up to 20% of the issued share capital.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The annual buyback program is up to US$1 billion.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In December 2025, it was announced AB InBev had acquired an 85% majority stake in the Austin, Texas-headquartered ready-to-drink (RTD) alcoholic beverages producer, BeatBox Beverages for approx.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The following is a diagram of AB InBev's major mergers and acquisitions and historical predecessors.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch InBev is controlled by Belgian families Vandamme, de Mévius and de Spoelberch, who as of 2015 owned a combined 28.6% of the company, and Brazilian investors Jorge Paulo Lemann, Carlos Alberto Sicupira and Marcel Telles, who owned 22.7% through their private investment firm 3G Capital.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] After the formation of Anheuser-Busch InBev SA/NV on 20 October 2016, the company was to be run by teams of "functional chiefs" and "zone presidents" who reported to AB InBev chief executive officer (CEO) Carlos Brito.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] All but one of those 19 positions are held by people who were already AB InBev executives before the acquisition of SABMiller.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Effective July 2021, Brito stepped down as the CEO of AB InBev after 15 years.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Michel Doukeris, previously CEO of North American business for Anheuser-Busch, succeeded him as CEO.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In October 2015, the company was investigated by the US Justice Department for buying beer distributors and preventing them from selling the beers of its competitors.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In September 2016, it was reported that AB InBev had paid a $6 million fine to the U.S.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Securities and Exchange Commission for violations of bribery laws under the Foreign Corrupt Practices Act and for silencing a whistleblower.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In May 2017, the company was criticized for reportedly engaging in anti-competitive practices after purchasing the entire supply of South African hops from SAB Hop Farms, as part of the SABMiller purchase, and making the hops unavailable to any US craft brewers.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Similar anti-competitive claims were also made in association with the company's purchase of Roseville, Minnesota-based Northern Brewer, the biggest homebrew-supply chain in the US, through AB Inbev's venture arm ZX Ventures.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The following month, the company was further criticized for having purchased a stake in the beer rating website RateBeer, leading to concerns that the purchase was a conflict of interest.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In July 2017, the company terminated its contract with "Casa Mia" pizzeria in Munich after the politician Ernst Dill tried to persuade the owner to ban Pegida supporters amongst his guests.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The year before Anheuser-Busch InBev already bound the owner of "Casa Mia" by contract to interpose at any sign of political activities.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] A company spokesperson said that the contract termination was not politically motivated.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In autumn 2018, AB InBev completed deals with Major League Baseball and the NBA which will allow it to use athletes' names and images when advertising.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] This is the first time in 60 years players will be seen in beer ads.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] On 21 March 2019, AB InBev subsidiary Anheuser-Busch was sued for false advertising by rival MillerCoors over a Bud Light commercial that aired during the 2019 Super Bowl.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The commercial claimed MillerCoors' Miller Lite and Coors Light products contain corn syrup, but the lawsuit argues that corn syrup is only used during the brewing process as a fermentation aid and neither beer contains corn syrup.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The suit alleges that Anheuser-Busch is using "false and misleading statements" to confuse health-conscious consumers into thinking the beers contain high-fructose corn syrup, which has been linked with obesity.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] An Anheuser-Busch spokesperson called the lawsuit "baseless" and said it would not deter Bud Light from "providing consumers with the transparency they demand." MillerCoors is seeking an injunction to prevent Bud Light from continuing the ad campaign, as well as a trial by jury and legal fees.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Since April 2023, AB InBev subsidiary Anheuser-Busch's Bud Light has faced an ongoing boycott from conservatives in the United States after having partnered with transgender influencer and activist Dylan Mulvaney.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] This has resulted in an ongoing major backlash and a boycott by the American right.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Anheuser-Busch CEO Brendan Whitworth attempted to walk back the partnership by saying, "We never intended to be part of a discussion that divides people.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] We are in the business of bringing people together over a beer." During the initial stage of the boycott, Anheuser-Busch issued a statement that marketing executive Alissa Heinerscheid had taken a leave of absence and would be replaced with its Vice President of Global Marketing, Todd Allen.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] A second executive, Daniel Blake, who was Heinerscheid's supervisor, was also placed on leave.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] An Anheuser-Busch spokesperson told The Wall Street Journal “Given the circumstances, Alissa has decided to take a leave of absence which we support.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] On 10 May 2023, HSBC downgraded Anheuser-Busch InBev stock as it dealt with a 'Bud Light crisis'.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] Analysts at HSBC cited “deeper problems than ABI admits” after a recent partnership with the transgender influencer Dylan Mulvaney resulted in a wave of backlash and a boycott.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] The analyst cited a Beer Marketer's Insights note that showed a steep drop in beer sales 'of maybe more than 25%' in April.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] In May 2023, AB InBev was named in Australia as one of three companies, along with Glencore and JBS, that used confidential tax information provided by PwC’s then head of international tax Peter Collins, which he obtained after consultations with treasury.
[src:bmw/ab-inbev] It was alleged that these companies acted on this information and restructured their operations to take advantage of new Multinational Anti-Avoidance Law (MAAL) introduced in 2016.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] Founded in 1987 by Willi Kohl and Herbert Schnitzer.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] Its range includes tuning for BMW vehicles and the Mini and Land Rover makes, and also a motorcycle arm.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] In addition to its customizing business, the firm's building in Aachen is home to several car firms, boutiques, and a luxury restaurant.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] The firm has roots with Schnitzer Motorsport, but is a completely independent company both commercially and legally.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] The core products offered by AC Schnitzer includes individual components such as chassis, custom exhaust systems, aerodynamic components, and light-alloy wheels, as well as complete vehicles and performance tuning for petrol and diesel engines.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] AC Schnitzer also makes products for vehicle interiors using materials such as aluminium, leather or carbon fibre.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] The product range includes control elements such as steering wheels, pedals and hand-brake levers, or interior mouldings and cladding, as well as to customer requirements.
[src:bmw/ac-schnitzer] AC Schnitzer is set to cease operations by 2027 due to mounting financial complications.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW AG's automobiles are marketed under the BMW, Mini, and Rolls-Royce brands while its motorcycles are marketed under the BMW Motorrad brand.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2023, BMW became the world's ninth-largest producer of motor vehicles (with 2,555,341 vehicles made in that year alone) as well as the 6th largest automaker by revenue.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2023, it was ranked 46th in the *Forbes* Global 2000.
[src:bmw/bmw] The company also has significant motor-sport history, especially in touring cars, sports cars, and the Isle of Man TT.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW initially focused on aircraft engine production during World War I, a legacy that influenced the company's engineering emphasis on performance and precision.
[src:bmw/bmw] Known as "The Ultimate Driving Machine", the brand is celebrated for engineering vehicles that blend high-end luxury with sharp, driver-focused performance.
[src:bmw/bmw] Following postwar restrictions on aircraft manufacturing, BMW diversified into motorcycle production in the 1920s and later entered the automobile market, establishing itself as a major player in the automotive industry.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW AG is headquartered in Munich and produces motor vehicles in Germany, United Kingdom, United States, Brazil, Mexico, South Africa, India, and China.
[src:bmw/bmw] The Quandt family is a long-term shareholder of the company, following investments by the brothers Herbert and Harald Quandt in 1959 which saved BMW from bankruptcy, with remaining shares owned by the public.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW traces its origins to aircraft engine manufacturer Otto Flugmaschinenfabrik, founded in 1910 by Gustav Otto in the Kingdom of Bavaria, then part of the German Empire.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 18 August 1916, the firm was reorganized as Bayerische Flugzeugwerke (BFW).
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1922, BFW was renamed Bayerische Motoren Werke (BMW).
[src:bmw/bmw] The name BMW, however, had earlier been used by a company founded in 1913 by Karl Rapp as Rapp Motorenwerke.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1922, the name and engine-production assets of Rapp Motorenwerke were transferred to Bayerische Flugzeugwerke, which adopted the BMW name in the same year.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW's first products were aircraft engines for the Luftstreitkräfte.
[src:bmw/bmw] One of its early designs was the BMW IIIa, a straight-six engine developed in 1917 by engineer Max Friz.
[src:bmw/bmw] After World War I, BMW diversified into the production of motorcycle engines, agricultural equipment, household items, and railway brakes.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1923, the company introduced its first motorcycle, the BMW R32.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW became an automobile manufacturer in 1928 following its acquisition of Fahrzeugfabrik Eisenach, which produced the Austin 7 under licence from Austin Motor Company, marketed as the Dixi.
[src:bmw/bmw] The first car sold as a BMW was the BMW 3/15, a rebadged version of the Dixi.
[src:bmw/bmw] During the 1930s, BMW expanded its product range to include sports cars and larger luxury vehicles.
[src:bmw/bmw] Aircraft engines, motorcycles, and automobiles would be BMW's main products until World War II.
[src:bmw/bmw] During the war, BMW concentrated on building the BMW 801 aircraft engine using as many as 40,000 slave laborers.
[src:bmw/bmw] These consisted primarily of prisoners from Nazi concentration camps, most prominently Dachau.
[src:bmw/bmw] Motorcycles remained as a side-line and automobile manufacture ceased altogether.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW's factories were heavily bombed during the war and its remaining West German facilities were banned from producing motor vehicles or aircraft after the war.
[src:bmw/bmw] The company survived by making pots, pans, and bicycles.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1948, BMW restarted motorcycle production.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW resumed car production in Bavaria in 1952 with the BMW 501 luxury saloon.
[src:bmw/bmw] The range of cars was expanded in 1955, through the production of the cheaper Isetta microcar under licence.
[src:bmw/bmw] Slow sales of luxury cars and small profit margins from microcars, meant BMW was in serious financial trouble and in 1959 the company was nearly taken over by rival Daimler-Benz.
[src:bmw/bmw] A large investment in BMW by Herbert Quandt and Harald Quandt resulted in the company surviving as a separate entity.
[src:bmw/bmw] Günther Quandt was a well-known German industrialist and joined the Nazi Party in 1933; he made a fortune arming the *Wehrmacht*, manufacturing weapons and batteries.
[src:bmw/bmw] Many of his enterprises were appropriated from Jewish owners under duress with minimal compensation.
[src:bmw/bmw] At least three of his enterprises made extensive use of slave laborers, as many as 50,000 in all.
[src:bmw/bmw] One of his battery factories had its own on-site concentration camp, complete with gallows.
[src:bmw/bmw] Life expectancy for laborers was six months.
[src:bmw/bmw] While Quandt and BMW were not directly connected during the war, funds amassed in the Nazi era by his father allowed Herbert Quandt to buy BMW.
[src:bmw/bmw] The relative success of the small BMW 700 assisted in the company's recovery, allowing them to develop the New Class sedans.
[src:bmw/bmw] The 1962 introduction of the BMW New Class compact sedans was the beginning of BMW's reputation as a leading manufacturer of sport-oriented cars.
[src:bmw/bmw] Throughout the 1960s, BMW expanded its range by adding coupé and luxury sedan models.
[src:bmw/bmw] The BMW 5 Series mid-size sedan range was introduced in 1972, followed by the BMW 3 Series compact sedans in 1975, the BMW 6 Series luxury coupés in 1976 and the BMW 7 Series large luxury sedans in 1978.
[src:bmw/bmw] The BMW M division released its first road car, the M1, a mid-engine supercar, in 1978.
[src:bmw/bmw] This was followed by the BMW M5 in 1984 and the BMW M3 in 1986.
[src:bmw/bmw] Also in 1986, BMW introduced its first V12 engine in the 750i luxury sedan.
[src:bmw/bmw] The 1989 BMW Z1 marked BMW's return to making a two-seat roadster, the 1995 BMW Z3 was their first mass-production two-seat roadster, and the 1999 BMW X5 was the company's first entry into the SUV market.
[src:bmw/bmw] The company purchased the Rover Group in 1994, but the takeover was not successful and caused BMW large financial losses.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2000, BMW sold off most of the Rover brands, retaining only the Mini brand.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1998, BMW also acquired the rights to the Rolls-Royce brand from Vickers.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW's first modern mass-produced turbocharged petrol engine was introduced in 2006 (from 1973 to 1975, BMW built 1,672 units of a turbocharged BMW M10 engine for the BMW 02 Series), with most engines switching over to turbocharging over the 2010s.
[src:bmw/bmw] The first hybrid BMW was the 2010 BMW ActiveHybrid 7, and BMW's first mass-production electric car was the BMW i3 city car, which was released in 2013, (from 1968 to 1972, BMW built two battery-electric BMW 1602 Elektro saloons for the 1972 Olympic Games).
[src:bmw/bmw] After many years of establishing a reputation for sporting rear-wheel drive cars, BMW's first front-wheel drive car was the 2014 BMW 2 Series Active Tourer multi-purpose vehicle (MPV).
[src:bmw/bmw] In March 2018, Daimler and BMW merged their mobility services.
[src:bmw/bmw] In August 2019, Oliver Zipse replaced Harald Krüger as the head of the BMW Group..
[src:bmw/bmw] In May 2026, Milan Nedeljković succeeded Zipse as chairman of the board of management of BMW AG.
[src:bmw/bmw] In January 2021, BMW announced that its sales in 2020 fell by 8.4 percent due to the impact of COVID-19 pandemic restrictions.
[src:bmw/bmw] However, in the fourth quarter of 2020, BMW witnessed a rise of 3.2% in its customers' demands.
[src:bmw/bmw] This recovery was supported by the company's adoption of widely accepted technologies and integration of third-party services such as Apple Pay and on-demand music as well as key partnerships such as its collaboration with Daimler on autonomous driving.
[src:bmw/bmw] Additionally, BMW's strategic investment decisions which include localizing production of its SUVs to the Spartanburg plant in the U.S., placed the group in a position to easily navigate trade challenges and shifting consumer patterns.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 18 January 2022 BMW announced a BMW 7 Series (G11) special edition simply called "The Final V12", the last BMW series production vehicle to be fitted with a V-12 engine.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 5 October 2023 it was announced that BMW UK CEO Chris Brownridge would succeed Torsten Müller-Ötvös as the CEO of Rolls-Royce starting 1 December 2023, as a result of Müller-Ötvös retiring.
[src:bmw/bmw] In January 2025, BMW announced the launch of a closed-loop recycling system for the reuse of raw materials from high-voltage batteries used in its range of electric vehicles.
[src:bmw/bmw] In November 2024, BMW launched a partnership in Europe with SK tes, a provider of solutions to recover cobalt, nickel and lithium from used batteries for use in making new batteries.
[src:bmw/bmw] In September 2025, BMW jointly developed an automated driving system with Qualcomm.
[src:bmw/bmw] In January 2026, the company was reported to be among the top 30 global investors in research and development (R&D) in 2025.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW is an abbreviation for *Bayerische Motoren Werke*.
[src:bmw/bmw] This name is grammatically incorrect (in German, compound words must not contain spaces), which is why the grammatically correct form of the name, *Bayerische Motorenwerke* (German pronunciation: [ˈbaɪʁɪʃə moˈtoːʁənˌvɛʁkə] ⓘ) has been used in several publications and advertisements in the past.
[src:bmw/bmw] *Bayerische Motorenwerke* translates into English as *Bavarian Motor Works*.
[src:bmw/bmw] The suffix AG, short for *Aktiengesellschaft*, signifies an incorporated entity owned by shareholders, akin to Inc., "Incorporated" (US) or PLC, "Public Limited Company" (UK).
[src:bmw/bmw] The terms Beemer, Bimmer and Bee-em are sometimes used as slang for BMW in the English language and are sometimes used interchangeably for cars and motorcycles.
[src:bmw/bmw] The circular blue and white BMW logo or roundel evolved from the circular *Rapp Motorenwerke* company logo, which featured a black ring bearing the company name surrounding the company logo, an image of a horse head on a plinth.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW retained Rapp's black ring inscribed with the company name, but the interior of the ring is quartered blue and white, reminiscent of the coat of arms and flag of Bavaria (which in turn are based on the arms of the historic House of Wittelsbach, which ruled Bavaria for many centuries).
[src:bmw/bmw] The logo does not bear the distinctive lozenge shape found on the coat of arms, however, as local laws at the time it was introduced forbade the use of state coats of arms on commercial logos.
[src:bmw/bmw] A persistent myth claims that the logo is based on the image of an airplane propeller spinning in a blue sky.
[src:bmw/bmw] This myth likely stems from a 1929 BMW advertisement that depicted the logo superimposed on a rotating propeller.
[src:bmw/bmw] However, the logo predates that advertisement by 12 years.
[src:bmw/bmw] The current iteration of the logo was introduced in 2020, removing 3D effects that had been used in previous renderings of the logo while removing the black outline encircling the roundel.
[src:bmw/bmw] The logo is used for BMW's branding communications but it is not used on vehicles.
[src:bmw/bmw] The slogan 'Freude am Fahren' (English: 'Sheer Driving Pleasure') has been used by BMW in most markets worldwide since 1972, when it was standardized as the company's official slogan and its English translation set for export markets.
[src:bmw/bmw] The slogan first appeared as 'Aus Freude am Fahren' in 1965 before the opening word was dropped in 1972.
[src:bmw/bmw] In the United States and United Kingdom, BMW instead uses 'The Ultimate Driving Machine'.
[src:bmw/bmw] The slogan 'The Ultimate Driving Machine' was coined by BMW North America in 1974, and first used in ads celebrating its win at the 1975 12 Hours of Sebring.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2010, this long-lived campaign was mostly supplanted by a campaign intended to make the brand more approachable and to better appeal to women, 'Joy'.
[src:bmw/bmw] By 2012 BMW had returned to 'The Ultimate Driving Machine'.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2023, the World Intellectual Property Organization (WIPO)’s Madrid Yearly Review ranked BMW's number of marks applications filled under the Madrid System as 2nd in the world, with 124 trademarks applications submitted during 2023.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW began production of motorcycle engines and then motorcycles after World War I.
[src:bmw/bmw] Its motorcycle brand is now known as BMW Motorrad.
[src:bmw/bmw] Their first successful motorcycle after the failed Helios and Flink, was the "R32" in 1923, though production originally began in 1921.
[src:bmw/bmw] This had a "boxer" twin engine, in which a cylinder projects into the air-flow from each side of the machine.
[src:bmw/bmw] Apart from its single-cylinder models (basically to the same pattern), all its motorcycles used this distinctive layout until the early 1980s.
[src:bmw/bmw] Many BMW's are still produced in this layout, which is designated the R Series.
[src:bmw/bmw] The entire BMW Motorcycle production line has, since 1969, been located at the company's Berlin-Spandau factory.
[src:bmw/bmw] During the Second World War, BMW produced the BMW R75 motorcycle with a motor-driven sidecar attached.
[src:bmw/bmw] Combined with a lockable differential, the vehicle was very capable off-road.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1982 came the K Series, with a shaft drive but water-cooled and with either three or four cylinders mounted in a straight line from front to back.
[src:bmw/bmw] Shortly after, BMW also started making the chain-driven F and G series with single and parallel twin Rotax engines.
[src:bmw/bmw] In the early 1990s, BMW updated the airhead Boxer engine which became known as the oilhead.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2002, the oilhead engine had two spark plugs per cylinder.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2004 it added a built-in balance shaft, an increased capacity to 1,170 cc (71 cu in) and enhanced performance to 75 kW (101 hp) for the R1200GS, compared to 63 kW (84 hp) of the previous R1150GS.
[src:bmw/bmw] More powerful variants of the oilhead engines are available in the R1100S and R1200S, producing 73 and 91 kW (98 and 122 hp), respectively.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2004, BMW introduced the new K1200S Sports Bike which marked a departure for BMW.
[src:bmw/bmw] It had an engine producing 125 kW (168 hp), derived from the company's work with the Williams F1 team, and is lighter than previous K models.
[src:bmw/bmw] Innovations include electronically adjustable front and rear suspension, and a Hossack-type front fork that BMW calls Duolever.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW introduced anti-lock brakes on production motorcycles starting in the late 1980s.
[src:bmw/bmw] The generation of anti-lock brakes available on the 2006 and later BMW motorcycles paved the way for the introduction of electronic stability control, or anti-skid technology later in the 2007 model year.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW has been an innovator in motorcycle suspension design, taking up telescopic front suspension long before most other manufacturers.
[src:bmw/bmw] Then it switched to an Earles fork, front suspension by swinging fork (1955 to 1969).
[src:bmw/bmw] Most modern BMWs are truly rear swingarm, single sided at the back (compare with the regular swinging fork usually, and wrongly, called swinging arm).
[src:bmw/bmw] Some BMWs started using yet another trademark front suspension design, the Telelever, in the early 1990s.
[src:bmw/bmw] Like the Earles fork, the Telelever significantly reduces dive under braking.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Group, on 31 January 2013, announced that Pierer Industrie AG has bought Husqvarna Motorcycles for an undisclosed amount, which will not be revealed by either party in the future.
[src:bmw/bmw] The company is headed by Stephan Pierer (CEO of KTM).
[src:bmw/bmw] Pierer Industrie AG is 51% owner of KTM and 100% owner of Husqvarna.
[src:bmw/bmw] In September 2018, BMW unveiled a new self-driving motorcycle with BMW Motorrad with a goal of using the technology to help improve road safety.
[src:bmw/bmw] The design of the bike was inspired by the company's BMW R1200 GS model.
[src:bmw/bmw] All-electric vehicles and plug-in hybrid vehicles are sold under the *BMW i* sub-brand.
[src:bmw/bmw] In addition, several plug-in hybrid models built on existing platforms have been marketed as *iPerformance* models.
[src:bmw/bmw] Examples include the 225xe using a 1.5 L three-cylinder turbocharged petrol engine with an electric motor, the 330e/530e using a 2.0 L four-cylinder engine with an electric motor, and the 550e/750e using a 3.0 L six-cylinder engine with an electric motor.
[src:bmw/bmw] Also, crossover and SUV plug-in hybrid models have been released using i technology: X1 xDrive25e, X2 xDrive25e, X3 xDrive30e, and X5 xDrive40e.
[src:bmw/bmw] The *BMW M GmbH* subsidiary (called BMW Motorsport GmbH until 1993) started making high-performance versions of various BMW models in 1978.
[src:bmw/bmw] The letter "M" is also often used in the marketing of BMW's regular models, for example the F20 M140i model, the G11 M760Li model and various optional extras called "M Sport", "M Performance" or similar.
[src:bmw/bmw] The global BMW Headquarters in Munich is designed after the cylinder head of a four-cylinder engine.
[src:bmw/bmw] It was designed by Karl Schwanzer and was completed in 1972.
[src:bmw/bmw] The building has become a European icon and was declared a protected historic building in 1999.
[src:bmw/bmw] The main tower consists of four vertical cylinders standing next to and across from each other.
[src:bmw/bmw] Each cylinder is divided horizontally in its center by a mold in the facade.
[src:bmw/bmw] Notably, these cylinders do not stand on the ground; they are suspended from a central support tower.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Museum is a futuristic cauldron-shaped building, which was also designed by Karl Schwanzer and opened in 1972.
[src:bmw/bmw] The interior has a spiral theme and the roof is a 40-metre diameter BMW logo.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Welt, the company's exhibition space in Munich, was designed by Coop Himmelb(l)au and opened in 2007.
[src:bmw/bmw] It includes a showroom and lifting platforms where a customer's new car is theatrically unveiled to the customer.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1975, sculptor Alexander Calder was commissioned to paint the BMW 3.0 CSL racing car driven by Hervé Poulain at the 24 Hours of Le Mans, which became the first in the series of BMW Art Cars.
[src:bmw/bmw] Since Calder's work of art, many other renowned artists throughout the world have created BMW Art Cars, including David Hockney, Jenny Holzer, Roy Lichtenstein, Robert Rauschenberg, Frank Stella, and Andy Warhol.
[src:bmw/bmw] To date, a total of 19 BMW Art Cars, based on both racing and regular production vehicles, have been created.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW sponsors a number of awards in the visual arts.
[src:bmw/bmw] These include the BMW Art Journey award, which honors a young or mid-career artist in collaboration with Art Basel, and the BMW Painting Award, which was created to promote painting in Spain by finding new talent and showcasing their work.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW was the principal sponsor of the 1998 *The Art of the Motorcycle* exhibition at various Guggenheim museums, though the financial relationship between BMW and the Guggenheim Foundation was criticised in many quarters.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2012, BMW began sponsoring Independent Collectors production of the *BMW Art Guide*, which is the first global guide to private and publicly accessible collections of contemporary art worldwide.
[src:bmw/bmw] The fourth edition, released in 2016, features 256 collections from 43 countries.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW also has local assembly operation using complete knock-down (CKD) components in Brazil, Thailand, Russia, Egypt, Indonesia, Malaysia and India.
[src:bmw/bmw] In the UK, BMW has a Mini factory near Oxford, plants in Swindon and Hams Hall, and Rolls-Royce vehicle assembly at Goodwood.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2020, these facilities were shut down for the period from 23 March to 17 April due to the coronavirus outbreak.
[src:bmw/bmw] The BMW group (including Mini and Rolls-Royce) produced 1,366,838 automobiles in 2006 and then 1,481,253 automobiles in 2010.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Motorcycles are being produced at the company's Berlin factory, which earlier had produced aircraft engines for Siemens.
[src:bmw/bmw] By 2011, about 56% of BMW-brand vehicles produced were powered by petrol engines and the remaining 44% by diesel engines.
[src:bmw/bmw] Of those petrol vehicles, about 27% were four-cylinder models and about nine percent are eight-cylinder models, the overwhelming majority being sixes.
[src:bmw/bmw] On average, 9,000 vehicles per day exit BMW plants, and 63% are transported by rail.
[src:bmw/bmw] In November 2016, BMW recalled 136,000 2007–2012 model year U.S. cars for fuel pump wiring problems possibly resulting in fuel leak and engine stalling or restarting issues.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2018, BMW recalled 106,000 diesel vehicles in South Korea with a defective exhaust gas recirculation module, which caused 39 engine fires.
[src:bmw/bmw] The recall was then expanded to 324,000 more cars in Europe.
[src:bmw/bmw] Following the recall in South Korea, the government banned cars which had not yet been inspected from driving on public roads.
[src:bmw/bmw] This affected up to 25% of the recalled cars, where the owners had been notified but the cars had not yet been inspected.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW is reported to have been aware since 2016 that more than 4% of the affected cars in South Korea had experienced failures in the EGR coolers, leading to approximately 20 owners suing the company.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW made a six-year sponsorship deal with the United States Olympic Committee in July 2010.
[src:bmw/bmw] In golf, BMW has sponsored various events, including the PGA Championship since 2007, the Italian Open from 2009 to 2012, the BMW Masters in China from 2012 to 2015 and the BMW International Open in Munich since 1989.
[src:bmw/bmw] In rugby, BMW sponsored the South Africa national rugby union team from 2011 to 2015.
[src:bmw/bmw] DriveNow was a joint-venture between BMW and Sixt that operated in Europe from 2011 until 2019.
[src:bmw/bmw] By December 2012, DriveNow operated over 1,000 vehicles, in five cities and with approximately 60,000 customers.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2012, the BMW-owned subsidiary Alphabet began a corporate car-sharing service in Europe called AlphaCity.
[src:bmw/bmw] The ReachNow car-sharing service was launched in Seattle in April 2016.
[src:bmw/bmw] ReachNow currently operates in Seattle, Portland and Brooklyn.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2018, BMW announced the launching of a pilot car subscription service for the United States called Access by BMW (its first one for the country), in Nashville, Tennessee.
[src:bmw/bmw] In January 2021, the company said that Access by BMW was "suspended".
[src:bmw/bmw] The first BMW production facility in China was opened in 2004, as a result of a joint venture between BMW and Brilliance Auto.
[src:bmw/bmw] The plant was opened in the Shenyang industrial area and produces 3 Series and 5 Series models for the Chinese market.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2012, a second factory was opened in Shenyang.
[src:bmw/bmw] Between January and November 2014, BMW sold 415,200 vehicles in China, through a network of over 440 BMW stores and 100 Mini stores.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 7 October 2021, BMW announced it would begin additional production of the X5 in China.
[src:bmw/bmw] In February 2022, BMW invested an additional $4.2 billion into the Chinese joint venture, increasing its stake from 50% to 75%, becoming one of the first foreign automakers holding majority stake in China.
[src:bmw/bmw] In June 2022, BMW announced a new plant project in Lydia, Shenyang designed for electric vehicles.
[src:bmw/bmw] It will become BMW Group's largest single project in China, costing 15 billion yuan (2.13 billion euros).
[src:bmw/bmw] The investment amount was raised by a further 10 billion yuan (US$1.4 billion) in November 2022, following German Chancellor Olaf Scholz's visit to China.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 31 July 2018, BMW announced to build a 1 billion euro car factory in Hungary.
[src:bmw/bmw] The plant, to be built near Debrecen, will have a production capacity of 150,000 cars a year.
[src:bmw/bmw] In July 2014, BMW announced it was establishing a plant in Mexico, in the city and state of San Luis Potosí involving an investment of $1 billion.
[src:bmw/bmw] The plant will employ 1,500 people, and produce 150,000 cars annually.
[src:bmw/bmw] The Mini Convertible, Mini Countryman and BMW X1 were produced in the Netherlands at the VDL Nedcar factory in Born up until its closure on February 16, 2024.
[src:bmw/bmw] The factory was closed after BMW did not renew its contract with VDL Nedcar.
[src:bmw/bmw] Long-term orders for the Mini Countryman ended in 2020.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMWs have been assembled in South Africa since 1968, when Praetor Monteerders' plant was opened in Rosslyn, near Pretoria.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW initially bought shares in the company, before fully acquiring it in 1975; in so doing, the company became *BMW South Africa*, the first wholly owned subsidiary of BMW to be established outside Germany.
[src:bmw/bmw] Unlike United States manufacturers, such as Ford and GM, which divested from the country in the 1980s, BMW retained full ownership of its operations in South Africa.
[src:bmw/bmw] Following the end of apartheid in 1994, and the lowering of import tariffs, BMW South Africa ended local production of the 5 Series and 7 Series, in order to concentrate on production of the 3 Series for the export market.
[src:bmw/bmw] South African–built BMWs are now exported to right hand drive markets including Japan, Australia, New Zealand, the United Kingdom, Indonesia, Malaysia, Singapore, and Hong Kong, as well as Sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:bmw/bmw] Since 1997, BMW South Africa has produced vehicles in left-hand drive for export to Taiwan, the United States and Iran, as well as South America.
[src:bmw/bmw] The plant code (position 11 in the VIN) for South African built models is "N".
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW cars have been officially sold in the United States since 1956 and manufactured in the United States since 1994.
[src:bmw/bmw] The first BMW dealership in the United States opened in 1975.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2016, BMW was the twelfth highest selling brand in the United States.
[src:bmw/bmw] The manufacturing plant in Greer, South Carolina has the highest production of the BMW plants worldwide, currently producing approximately 1,500 vehicles per day.
[src:bmw/bmw] The models produced at the Spartanburg plant are the X3, X4, X5, X6, X7 and XM SUV models.
[src:bmw/bmw] In addition to the South Carolina manufacturing facility, BMW's North American companies include sales, marketing, design, and financial services operations in the United States, Mexico, Canada and Latin America.
[src:bmw/bmw] On 9 October 2014, BMW's new complete knock-down (CKD) assembly plant in Araquari, assembled its first car— an F30 3 Series.
[src:bmw/bmw] The cars assembled at Araquari are the F20 1 Series, F30 3 Series, F48 X1, F25 X3 and Mini Countryman.
[src:bmw/bmw] Bavarian Auto Group became the importer of the BMW and Mini brands in 2003.
[src:bmw/bmw] Since 2005, the 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1 and X3 models sold in Egypt are assembled from complete knock-down components at the BMW plant in Cairo.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW India was established in 2006 as a sales subsidiary with a head office located in Gurugram.
[src:bmw/bmw] A BMW complete knock-down assembly plant was opened in Chennai in 2007, assembling Indian-market 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1, X3, X5, Mini Countryman and motorcycle models.
[src:bmw/bmw] The 20 Million Euro plant aims to produce 1,700 cars per year.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Indonesia was established in 2001 as a subsidiary with a head office located in Central Jakarta.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW's complete knock-down (CKD) assembly plant in Kedah.
[src:bmw/bmw] Assembled Malaysia-market 1 Series, 3 Series, 5 Series, 7 Series, X1, X3, X4, X5, X6 and Mini Countryman since 2008.
[src:bmw/bmw] Russian-market 3 Series and 5 Series cars are assembled from complete knock-down components in Kaliningrad beginning in 1999.
[src:bmw/bmw] In March 2022, BMW withdrew from the Russian market, ceased new car sales in Russia, and ceased production within Russia, in response to the Russian invasion of Ukraine.
[src:bmw/bmw] In Uruguay, Spanish-born businessman José Arijón founded Convex (later Camur), which assembled BMW cars from 1965 to 1992.
[src:bmw/bmw] Four models were produced: the 1600, 2002, 3 Series and 5 Series, totalling 12,000 units.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW's first dealership in Canada, located in Ottawa, was opened in 1969.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 1986, BMW established a head office in Canada.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW sold 28,149 vehicles in Canada in 2008.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Japan Corp, a wholly owned subsidiary, imports and distributes BMW vehicles in Japan.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Philippines, an owned subsidiary of San Miguel Corporation, is the official importer and distributor of BMW in the Philippines.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW sold 920 vehicles in the Philippines in 2019.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Korea imports BMW vehicles in South Korea with more than fifty service centers to fully cater to South Korean customers.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW Korea has its own driving center near Incheon International Airport.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW car represented almost 10% of all new cars registered in 2025, making it the third most popular car brand.
[src:bmw/bmw] BMW has received criticism for attempting to lock vehicle hardware features behind subscription fees.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2018, BMW stated at the Detroit Auto Show that it will start charging users a subscription fee for Apple Car Play.
[src:bmw/bmw] After receiving widespread criticism, BMW removed the subscription.
[src:bmw/bmw] In 2022, BMW announced that it will start charging owners $18 a month to use heated seats.
[src:bmw/bmw] They removed the feature in 2023 after it was criticised.
